<seg id="1">Report on the results of parallel checks on the management of value added tax between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic carried out in 2005</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">The submitted material informs about the progress and results of parallel checks carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the NajA Supervisory Office of the Slovak Republic, which were focused on the area of value added tax management and the use of the VIES information system (Value Added Tax Information Exchange System).</seg>
<seg id="4">In May 2004, the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic joined the European Union, so revenues from value added tax affect not only the state budgets of both countries, but also the budget of the European Union as a whole.</seg>
<seg id="5">Parallel control actions were aimed in particular at checking the procedure of the tax authorities in examining the amount of value added tax paid in commercial transactions carried out between individual Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="6">The introduction of the VIES system enabled the electronic exchange of information on the registration of VAT payers in individual Member States of the European Union and on commercial transactions carried out by these payers.</seg>
<seg id="7">The mismatch between the VIES data and the data in the VAT return submitted by the payer should alert the tax authorities to suspicious cases and allow the detection of tax evasion or fraud.</seg>
<seg id="8">The benefits of the parallel checks carried out consisted not only in the exchange of information on the progress of financial or tax authorities in the management of value added tax, but in particular in examining the use of the VIES system in checking the application of the right to an exemption from value added tax in intracomonality transactions.</seg>
<seg id="9">The lessons learned in the implementation of parallel controls are beneficial for the development of mutual cooperation and will be used in carrying out further parallel controls in cooperation with the control institutions of the Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="10">Report on the results of parallel checks on the management of value added tax for the period from 1 January 2004 to 30 June 2005</seg>
<seg id="11">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="12">Control number: (CZ) 05/19 (SK) 22/2005</seg>
<seg id="13">Subject of scrutiny: (CZ) Value Added Tax Administration, (SK) Control of the procedure of tax authorities in the administration, control and enforcement of value added tax and fulfilment of roles under VIES for the exchange of information between EU Member States</seg>
<seg id="14">The Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the SAO, the Czech Republic) and the Najvyšší Control Office of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the SAO of the Slovak Republic) concluded the Cooperation in Control Activities on 12 December 2005.</seg>
<seg id="15">The subject of the contract was cooperation in the implemented parallel control actions of the "Value Added Tax Administration", included in the control activity plan of the SAO, the Czech Republic for 2005 under No 05/19 and "Control of the procedure of the tax authorities in spiral, control and recovery of dane from the pridé value and pleneni roles within the VIES system on the fabric of information media by the member regions of the ECO", included in the control activity plan of the SAO SR SAO under No 22/2005.</seg>
<seg id="16">Parallel control actions carried out were in the nature of coordinated checks.</seg>
<seg id="17">The outcome of the joint coordinated control was drawn up within the meaning of European Implementing Regulation No 31 for INTOSAI control standards.</seg>
<seg id="18">The cooperation consisted of exchanging information to the extent provided for in the contract and in drawing up a joint final report on the outcome of parallel checks.</seg>
<seg id="19">The purpose of the coordinated check was to verify selected cases of delivery and acquisition of goods in suspicious commercial transactions between value added tax payers from the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the Czech Republic) and the Slovak Republic (SR).</seg>
<seg id="20">The two parties have contracted to provide each other with information from public sources, the VIES electronic system (Value Added Tax Information Exchange System) and data on received and sent requests to investigate business transactions between the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="21">The checks were carried out in parallel between June and December 2005.</seg>
<seg id="22">On the territory of the Czech Republic, the inspection was carried out by the State Budget Department and the territorial unions of Central Bohemia, northwest Bohemia, southern Bohemia, South Moravia, central Moravia and northern Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited bodies were the Ministry of Finance and 12 Financial Offices: Financial Office in Mladá Boleslav, Financial Office in Cologne, Financial Office in Teplice, Financial Office in Karlovy Vary, Financial Office in Tábor, Financial Office Brno III, Financial Office in Znojmo, Financial Office in Zlín, Financial Office in Šumperk, Financial Office Ostrava I, Financial Office for Prague 7 and Financial Office for Prague 9.</seg>
<seg id="24">The audit on the territory of the SR was carried out by the Financial and Tax Section of the SAO SR in cooperation with Expoziturami SAO SR Banská Bystrica and Košice on 9 selected tax offices: Tax Úrad Bratislava I, Tax Úrad Komárno, Tax Úrad Trenčín, Tax Office Prievidza, Tax Úrad Zvolen, Tax Úrad Dolný Kubín, Tax Úrad Košice II, Tax Úrad Košice V and Tax Úrad Michalovce.</seg>
<seg id="25">Objective of checks:</seg>
<seg id="26">The aim of parallel control actions was to examine the procedure of financial or tax authorities in the management of value added tax (VAT) after the integration of the Czech Republic and Slovakia into the single internal market of the European Union (EU) and to examine the use of the VIES electronic information system, in particular when checking the application of the right to VAT exemption.</seg>
<seg id="27">The audited period for coordinated control was the period from 1 May 2004 to 30 June 2005.</seg>
<seg id="28">Summary of the results and evaluation of parallel control actions In the EU Member States, an electronic VIES system is in place, allowing tax administrations to check whether the supplier has been entitled to exempt taxable transactions from VAT and makes it possible to check in the country of destination whether the purchaser has properly admitted and taxed the acquired goods.</seg>
<seg id="29">VIES is not centralised within the EU, each Member State is developing its own system.</seg>
<seg id="30">The checks identified differences in the national VIES systems in the Czech Republic and Slovakia in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="31">The recapitulative statements shall indicate the values of deliveries of goods to other EU Member States, the values of the services provided shall not be included in the recapitulative statements.</seg>
<seg id="32">Data from recapitulative statements submitted by Czech payers are processed in the Czech Republic at the level of the tax authorities, where they are compared with data on supplies of goods to other EU Member States listed in VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="33">The tax authorities shall transmit the data from the recapitulative statements to the Ministry of Finance (CLO), which sends them to other EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="34">In Slovakia, data from recapitulative statements filed by Slovak payers at tax offices are only converted into electronic form and processed centrally at the Slovak Tax Directorate (CLO).</seg>
<seg id="35">In the Czech Republic, payers report the value of the supply of goods and the value of the provision of services to other EU Member States on separate lines of VAT returns, which makes it possible to compare the values given in the recapitulative reports with the values of the supply of goods according to VAT tax returns and to identify their possible differences.</seg>
<seg id="36">In the SR, the values of goods delivered and services supplied to other EU Member States are reported cumulatively on the common row of the VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="37">As a result, the system does not make it possible to automatically identify differences between the values of the supply of goods under VAT returns and recapitulative statements.</seg>
<seg id="38">Separate reporting of the values of the supply of goods in VAT tax returns makes it possible to use the results of the comparison of data when checking the exemption of goods to the EU from VAT.</seg>
<seg id="39">The supplied data from the recapitulative statements submitted by the payers in other EU Member States are processed into the CLO and compared with the value of the acquisition of goods mentioned by the payers from the Czech Republic or Slovakia in VAT tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="40">In the SR, these figures are sent to the tax authorities and the tax authorities themselves decide which cases of differences to examine.</seg>
<seg id="41">In the Czech Republic, the Ministry of Finance (CLO) will determine the quantified differences between the values of delivery and the acquisition of goods must be examined by the tax authorities, and hand over a list of these cases to the locally competent tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="42">This ensures that for the most significant derogations, it will be examined whether VAT has been awarded at the correct amount when acquiring the goods.</seg>
<seg id="43">The audit also highlighted some of the problems in the VAT management system of the complications caused by the different reporting of intracomonality transactions (i.e. the supply and acquisition of goods made by payers from different EU Member States):</seg>
<seg id="44">Summary reports are made in the EU for each calendar quarter and the maximum time limit for processing and sending data to other EU Member States is set at 3 months from the end of the relevant quarter.</seg>
<seg id="45">Reducing the period for which recapitulative statements are made for one month, together with the shortening of the deadline for processing them, would allow earlier access to the VIES data.</seg>
<seg id="46">Tax administrators would thus be able to examine more effectively whether VAT was awarded at the correct amount in intracomonarian acquisitions.</seg>
<seg id="47">At the same time, filing VAT returns and recapitulative statements for the same tax year (month) would allow faster verification of whether the payer has reported the same values of the supply of goods to the EU in the recapitulative statement as well as the VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="48">The differences between the values of delivery of goods reported by EU payers and the values of the acquisition of goods reported by payers from the Czech Republic or SR were due, among other things, to different reporting of data on intracomonality delivery and acquisition in individual EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="49">These included, for example, the inclusion of received advances in the recapitulative reports, or the reporting of intracomonant supplies in the supplier's recapitulative statement in a quarter other than intracomonality acquisitions in the tax return on the purchaser's VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="50">A unification of the conditions for reporting these data within the EU would lead to streamlining the control activity of national tax administrations.</seg>
<seg id="51">The cooperation of the SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO SR was also aimed at examining selected intracomonality transactions carried out between the two states.</seg>
<seg id="52">Together, a total of 40 cases of commercial transactions carried out between 29 Czech and 32 Slovak tax entities were examined, for which there were doubts about their realisation or suspicion of tax evasion on VAT.</seg>
<seg id="53">The SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO of the SR found, among other things, the following facts:</seg>
<seg id="54">the tax authorities have declared in their VAT returns in order to unlawfully obtain excess VAT execution of intracomonant transactions which have not actually been carried out;</seg>
<seg id="55">tax entities reported intracomonality supplies in carousel transactions in which there was a deliberate multiple reduction in the value of supplies in order to draw on excess VAT deductions;</seg>
<seg id="56">the suppliers reported in their VAT tax returns and recapitulative statements the intracomonality supply of goods exempt from VAT to purchasers who were so-called "lost companies" and did not declare the tax on the goods acquired;</seg>
<seg id="57">the suppliers made an intracomonality supply of goods exempt from VAT for tax entities that were not registered for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="58">In such cases, the supply should not have been exempt from VAT and should have been subject to tax in the supplier's country;</seg>
<seg id="59">suppliers reported intracomonality supplies in their VAT tax returns at a higher value than those declared by the purchasers of the intracomonality acquisition, in some cases the VAT was declared in the wrong amount.</seg>
<seg id="60">The findings of the inspection showed that the VIES system provides tax administrations with the information necessary to check the correct application of VAT in intracomonality transactions.</seg>
<seg id="61">In particular, tax administrations should pay extra attention to the rigorous examination of the differences between the data reported by VAT payers and the VIES data and the use of all information in tax procedures.</seg>
<seg id="62">The issue of value added tax after the entry of the Czech Republic and Slovakia into the EU</seg>
<seg id="63">Value added tax</seg>
<seg id="64">On 1 May 2004, the Czech Republic and Slovakia became members of the EU.</seg>
<seg id="65">After joining the EU, internal borders and border controls on the movement of goods within EU territory were abolished.</seg>
<seg id="66">The VAT administrator was the relevant financial or tax office until 30.4.2004, with the exception of the import of goods and occasional bus transport in the Czech Republic, where the tax administrator was the customs office.</seg>
<seg id="67">In connection with the adoption of the new Act No 235/2004 Coll., on Value Added Tax (hereinafter referred to as "Law No. 235/2004 Coll.), or Act No. 222/2004 Z. z., on Pridanej Value Tax (hereinafter referred to as "Law No 222/2004 Z. z."), the VAT administration switched the acquisition of goods and services (formerly imports) from other EU Member States from customs offices to financial or tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="68">The delivery of goods in the Czech Republic under the provisions of Section 13 of Act No. 235/2004 Coll. means the transfer of the right to dispose of the goods as owner.</seg>
<seg id="69">The delivery of goods from the Czech Republic to another EU Member State is the delivery of goods that have actually been shipped or transported to another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="70">Pursuant to the provisions of Section 64 of Act No 235/2004 Coll., it is an exempt taxable transaction with a right to deduct VAT if the goods are supplied to a person registered for VAT in another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="71">The supply of goods in the Slovak Republic under the provisions of Section 8 of Law No 222/2004 Z. z. is considered to be the supply of tangible property in which ownership rights are changed.</seg>
<seg id="72">The transfer of goods belonging to a taxable person from the country to another Member State shall also be considered a supply of goods if those goods are dispatched or transported by that person or on his behalf to another Member State for the purposes of his business.</seg>
<seg id="73">Under Paragraph 43 of Law No 222/2004 Z. z., the supply of goods from the country to another Member State is exempt from VAT if the person acquiring the person identified for VAT in another Member State is the person identified for VAT.</seg>
<seg id="74">The acquisition of goods from another EU Member State in the Czech Republic under the provisions of Section 16 of Act No 235/2004 Coll. means the acquisition of the right to dispose as owner of the goods which are sent or transported by a person registered for VAT in another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="75">The Czech payer buys goods at a price without VAT and his obligation is to declare VAT in the Czech Republic under the provisions of Section 25 of Act No 235/2004 Coll., subject to the fulfilment of the conditions set out in Section 73 of this Act, he is entitled to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="76">By acquiring goods domestically from another EU Member State, in the Slovak Republic, pursuant to the provisions of Section 11 of Law No 222/2004 Z. z., the acquisition of the right to dispose as owner of movable tangible property dispatched or transported by the purchaser by the supplier or the acquirer or on their behalf to the country from another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="77">The tax liability in the SR arises to the payer when acquiring goods in the Czech Republic from another Member State under the provisions of Section 20 of Law No 222/2004 Z.z.</seg>
<seg id="78">The payer may deduct VAT under the provisions of Section 49 of Law No 222/2004 Z. if the tax is applied by it when acquiring goods in the national territory from another Member State pursuant to the provisions of Sections 11 and 11a of this Act.</seg>
<seg id="79">Trilateral trade means, according to the provisions of Section 17 of Act No 235/2004 Coll., or Section 45 of Act No 222/2004 Z. trade concluded between three persons registered for VAT in three different EU Member States, where the subject of trade is the supply of the same goods between the three persons.</seg>
<seg id="80">Intracomonarial transactions means the supply and acquisition of goods made between VAT payers from different EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="81">The total volumes of intracomonality transactions carried out between the Czech Republic and Slovakia are shown in the following table.</seg>
<seg id="82">VIES</seg>
<seg id="83">In order to check the application of the VAT exemption entitlement to intracommunity supplies of goods, a VAT information exchange system has been established within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="84">It includes the VIES electronic system, which allows tax administrations of EU Member States to check whether the supplier was entitled to exempt taxable transactions from VAT and vice versa whether the acquirer duly admitted and taxed the acquired goods.</seg>
<seg id="85">The VIES information system is not centralised within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="86">Each Member State shall develop its own VIES system.</seg>
<seg id="87">National systems work on a common principle and are interconnected through the EU's common communication network, the so-called CCN (Common Communication Network; see diagram below).</seg>
<seg id="88">In the Czech Republic, the VIES system was linked to an automated tax information system (ADIS), in the Slovak Republic, with the application software of the tax information system (hereinafter referred to as "APV DIS").</seg>
<seg id="89">These systems use financial or tax authorities as technical support for executive and management activities in tax and fee management.</seg>
<seg id="90">International administrative cooperation</seg>
<seg id="91">Through international administrative cooperation, the tax administration of each EU member country receives information on tax entities that it would not have been able to obtain on its own without such cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="92">The main objective of international administrative cooperation is to combat tax evasion and tax losses.</seg>
<seg id="93">Pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003, each Member State, within the internal organisational structure, provides for a central unit in the field of administrative cooperation between EU Member States in the administration of VAT, the so-called CLO (CLO (Central Liaison Office).</seg>
<seg id="94">In the Czech Republic, the Ministry of Finance – the Central Financial and Tax Directorate, where the International Cooperation in the VAT Administration (MF CLO) was established.</seg>
<seg id="95">The CLO function in the Slovak Republic is performed by the Slovak Tax Directorate, the International Administrative Cooperation Unit (DR CLO).</seg>
<seg id="96">These departments inter alia communicate with EU foreign administrations, in particular in the area of exchange of information under the VIES system, the exchange of spontaneous information and information at the request of EU tax administrations, the coordination of multilateral (simultaneous) tax controls, the verification of tax identification numbers (hereinafter referred to as the VAT Code) of persons registered for VAT in other EU Member States and communicate with the European Commission.</seg>
<seg id="97">In order to examine a certain intracomonality transaction or to obtain other information relating to a particular tax entity, the financial or tax authorities shall send requests for information to the EU via the IF CLO or DR CLO to the EU.</seg>
<seg id="98">Through these applications, they obtain from the requested Member States information which they can use to correctly determine VAT.</seg>
<seg id="99">Requests for information are mostly sent between the CLO of EU Member States in electronic form, using the standardised SCAC form.</seg>
