<seg id="356">Cooperation in the field of information exchange is governed by Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003.</seg>
<seg id="357">The maximum time limit for replying to the ROI was set in Article 8 of this Regulation for 3 months.</seg>
<seg id="358">The conditions for admissibility of applications are governed by the Decision of the Commission of the European Communities of 15.11.2004, which provides that, unless the participating States agree otherwise, the RHI must relate to commercial transactions worth at least EUR 1 500 excluding VAT.</seg>
<seg id="359">Where the ROI relates to a commercial transaction of less than EUR 15 000 excluding VAT, the requested authority may refuse to respond in view of its workload.</seg>
<seg id="360">The procedure for processing received ŽOI by the tax administration of the Czech Republic, including the indication of internal time limits set for processing at individual organizational levels, illustrates the following diagram.</seg>
<seg id="361">In the SR, the deadline for the processing of ŽOI by the tax authorities was set internally for 2 months so that the three-month period under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 could be met.</seg>
<seg id="362">MF CLO received a total of 29 ŽOI and 3 SPI from SR from 1 May 2004 to 30 June 2005.</seg>
<seg id="363">Of the 29 ŽOI received, 26 (i.e. 89.7%) were processed within the time limit of 3 months and 3 (i.e. 10.3%) were dealt with after that period.</seg>
<seg id="364">In the same period, DR CLO from the Czech Republic received a total of 71 ŽOI and 7 SPI.</seg>
<seg id="365">Of the 71 ŽOI received, 64 (i.e. 90.1%) were processed within the deadline of 3 months, 5 (i.e. 7.0%) were dealt with after that period (for the other 2 cases, it was not possible to determine the processing time from the submitted materials).</seg>
<seg id="366">More detailed data on the time of processing of ŽOI received MF CLO or DR CLO contains the following chart.</seg>
<seg id="367">The reasons for sending the ŽOI, given on the SCAC forms, are provided in the following table.</seg>
<seg id="368">Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="369">On the basis of international cooperation, compliance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 on administrative cooperation in the field of VAT has been examined, as well as the use of the VIES system to exchange information between EU Member States, in particular when checking the application of the right to VAT exemption.</seg>
<seg id="370">International cooperation made it possible to examine selected intracomonality transactions carried out between VAT payers from the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="371">By examining the selected transactions, it was found that, on the basis of an international exchange of information, the tax administrations of both countries revealed cases of companies that carried out fictitious intracomonal commercial transactions to obtain excess VAT deductions, as well as cases where the purchasers did not declare VAT on the received supplies of goods at the correct amount.</seg>
<seg id="372">Furthermore, the checks identified differences in the processing and use of VIES data by the tax administrations of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="373">The audit also highlighted the problems caused by different reporting of data on intracomonality deliveries and purchases of goods in individual EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="374">A unification of the conditions for reporting these data within the EU would lead to streamlining the control activity of national tax administrations.</seg>
<seg id="375">By examining the procedure of the financial or tax authorities in the administration of VAT and the use of the VIES system, it was found that the financial or tax authorities did not sufficiently use all the possibilities of the VIES system and the relevant legal permissions.</seg>
<seg id="376">Furthermore, it was found that the VIES did not provide up-to-date information on the supply of goods and the validity of the VAT registration of tax entities in all cases.</seg>
<seg id="377">The SAO SR compared data on the occurrence of erroneous data in SH, processed before the start of the inspection performance, with data processed after the completion of the inspection performance.</seg>
<seg id="378">It was clear from the comparison of these data that the audit of the SAO of the SR had an impact not only on the reduction of the number of SHs with the erroneous VAT number, but also on the reduction of the number of unrepaired errors in SH.</seg>
<seg id="379">In the case of irregularities in the reported data of the SAO SR, it asked the tax authorities to carry out local investigations or to carry out tax inspections.</seg>
<seg id="380">The SAO, the Czech Republic did not have such an option under the current legislation in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="381">The findings of the control actions obtained showed that the VIES system provided tax administrations with the basic information necessary to check the correct application of VAT in intracomonality transactions.</seg>
<seg id="382">As there continues to be scope for tax evasion in this area, there is a need for increased attention to intracomonality transactions in the VAT administration.</seg>
<seg id="383">Communications</seg>
<seg id="384">This report was prepared in the Czech, English and Slovak languages and signed by the President of the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the chairman of Najýššie's control department of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
</p>
