<p>
<seg id="1">Parallel control of the administration of value added tax and excise duty between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">This information material gives an overview of the progress and results of parallel control actions carried out by the Supreme Audit Office and the Najk control úradom of the Slovak Republic, which were focused on the management of value added and excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="4">Cooperation between the highest control authorities of both countries was implemented on the basis of a cooperation agreement in control activities concluded in February 2004.</seg>
<seg id="5">The subject of parallel control actions has been selected in view of the fact that indirect taxes account for a significant contribution to the revenues of the two countries' state budgets.</seg>
<seg id="6">The design of value added tax, allowing the refund of excess deduction, provides scope for tax fraud or evasion.</seg>
<seg id="7">High excise duty rates, especially for tobacco and tobacco products, alcohol and mineral oils, mean high profits for those who escape taxation by illegally selling these goods.</seg>
<seg id="8">Tax fraud is a problem not only in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, but also in other European Union countries.</seg>
<seg id="9">Due to the need to address this issue comprehensively across the European Union, the highest control institutions of the European Union Member States have been set up by the VAT Working Group, in whose activities the highest control offices of both countries are actively involved.</seg>
<seg id="10">The greatest benefit of the control actions carried out can be seen not only in the exchange of experience, but in particular in a joint effort to identify problem areas of indirect tax administration in order to limit the scope for tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="11">The experience gained and knowledge will be used in the framework of planned indirect tax inspections, mainly aimed at involving both Member States' tax administrations in the VIES system, to control the movement of goods between the Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="12">Report on the results of the control of the management of value added tax and excise duties for the period 2002 and 2003</seg>
<seg id="13">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="14">Control number: (CZ) 04/07 (SK) 18/2004</seg>
<seg id="15">Subject-matter of the inspection:</seg>
<seg id="16">(CZ) Value added tax and excise duty</seg>
<seg id="17">(SK) Control of the procedure of the tax administrator in the administration, control and recovery of value added tax and excise duty</seg>
<seg id="18">On 11.2.2004 the Cooperation Agreement was concluded in control activities between the Supreme Audit Office (hereinafter referred to as the SAO) and the Najvyšší audit úradom of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the "SAO of the Slovak Republic"). The subject of the contract was cooperation in the implemented parallel control actions "Value added tax and excise duty tax", included in the auditing plan of the SAO for 2004 under No 04/07 and "Control of the procedure of the administration dane pri správe, control and recovery of dane from the pridé value and spotreb taxes", included in the control activity plan of the SAO SR under No 18/2004.</seg>
<seg id="19">The cooperation consisted of exchanging information to the extent provided for in the contract and in drawing up a joint final report on the outcome of the checks.</seg>
<seg id="20">In the contract, the two parties undertook to provide each other with information from public sources, from the customs administration database and from the files of tax entities held by the tax authorities in the Czech Republic and tax authorities in the Slovak Republic, which the contracting parties were unable to obtain when checking the application of value added tax and excise duties on imports and exports from sources in the territory of the relevant state.</seg>
<seg id="21">The checks were carried out in parallel between January and August 2004.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the territory of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the Czech Republic), the inspection was carried out by the State Budget Department and the territorial unions of southern Bohemia, northeastern Bohemia, South Moravia, Central Moravia and northern Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited persons were the General Directorate of Customs and 12 selected Financial Offices: Financial Office for Prague 1, Financial Office for Prague 3, Financial Office in České Budějovice, Financial Office in Frýdek-Místek, Financial Office in Hodonín, Financial Office in Jihlava, Financial Office in Kostelec nad Orlicí, Financial Office in Kroměříž, Financial Office in Písek, Financial Office in Rožnov pod Radhoštěm, Financial Office in Ústí nad Orlicí, Financial Office in Velke Meziříčí.</seg>
<seg id="24">The audit on the territory of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the "SR") was carried out by the Section of Tax and Customs Administration of the SAO of the SR in cooperation with Exposituras of the SAO SR Banská Bystrica and Košice at 10 selected tax offices:</seg>
<seg id="25">Tax Úrad Bratislava pre selected tax entities, Tax Úrad Bratislava III, Tax Úrad Trnava, Tax Úrad Pú-chov, Tax Úrad Banská Bystrica I, Tax Úrad Liptovský Mikuláš, Tax Úrad Žilina I, Tax Úrad Žilina I, Tax Úrad Žilina II, Tax Úrad Košice I and Tax Úrad Košice IV.</seg>
<seg id="26">Objective of control</seg>
<seg id="27">The aim of the control actions was to examine the fulfilment of the obligations of financial or tax authorities and customs offices in the administration of value added tax and excise duty, with a focus on the collection of these taxes on the import and export of goods and services.</seg>
<seg id="28">The aim of international cooperation was to verify imports and exports of selected commodities between the Czech Republic and Slovakia in the customs database of the Czech Republic and their subsequent verification in tax returns at the relevant financial or tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="29">The audited period was 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="30">2. Recapitulation of control results</seg>
<seg id="31">2.1. 2.1. General evaluation of control activities</seg>
<seg id="32">As part of the SAO's international cooperation, the SAO of the Slovak Republic handed over 22,206 items of uniform customs declarations (hereinafter referred to as "JCD") on imports and exports of goods between the Czech Republic and Slovakia, and vice versa, the SAO of the SR, handed over 30 221 JCD items from the SR customs database.</seg>
<seg id="33">A comparison of the drafted JCD items from the customs database of the Czech Republic and the customs database of the Slovak Republic was made.</seg>
<seg id="34">Of the 5 883 selected JCD items from the customs database of the Czech Republic, a total of 43% of the related JCD items were assigned.</seg>
<seg id="35">Of the 12,343 selected JCD items from the SR customs database, a total of 26% of the related JCD entries were assigned.</seg>
<seg id="36">Based on the unassigned JCD items, financial or tax offices selected files of tax entities for which reported imports and exports were further verified in cooperation with the customs administrations of the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="37">Based on the exchange of information from the documents of the customs administrations of the Czech Republic and the Slovak and financial or tax authorities, the implementation of reported imports and exports between the Czech Republic and Slovakia was verified on the territory of the second state.</seg>
<seg id="38">The SAO and the SAO of the Slovak Republic carried out a joint pilot inspection at the border customs crossing Starý Hrozenkov - Drietoma, in which the two interested parties cooperated closely in verifying the accuracy of data on the movement of goods between the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="39">The inspection did not identify deficiencies in the register of selected cases of imports and exports of goods carried out in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="40">International cooperation has made it possible to examine trade transactions carried out between trading partners from both states and pointed to shortcomings in the import and export records.</seg>
<seg id="41">2.2. Summary of the results of the inspection</seg>
<seg id="42">Control of the SAO and SAO SR in the field of international cooperation focused on imports and exports of spirits and spirits, tobacco and tobacco products, computers and computer components, mobile phones and their components, and possibly other types of goods.</seg>
<seg id="43">On the basis of an examination of the files of tax entities at selected financial or tax offices, the SAO asked for verification of the implementation of exports of goods declared at 40 JCD with a total statistical value of CZK 15,010,093 and the SAO SR to verify exports at a statistical value of 56 989 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="44">The SAO and the SAO of the SR found, among other things, the following facts:</seg>
<seg id="45">- trade transactions were not declared in the same way on both sides, which made it difficult to identify the corresponding imports and exports in the customs database of the Czech Republic and the SR customs database,</seg>
<seg id="46">- the error rate in entering data in customs databases made it impossible to identify certain imports or exports,</seg>
<seg id="47">- for some exports from the Czech Republic, corresponding imports into the Slovak Republic have not been demonstrated.</seg>
<seg id="48">In such cases, there is a reasonable suspicion of fictitious exports of goods for the purpose of unauthorising application of value added tax deductions,</seg>
<seg id="49">- Tax entities did not comply with certain statutory obligations when reporting imports and exports in value added tax returns,</seg>
<seg id="50">- deficiencies were identified in the activities of financial or tax authorities in the management of value added tax and excise duties and in their interaction with the customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="51">In the area of value added tax and excise duties, attention will continue to need to be paid to international trade in order to effectively minimise tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="52">In particular, it is important to improve the activities of tax administrators in the exercise of value added tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="53">The basis for effective control of excise duties is to check the circulation of documents, systematic physical control of goods and the mutual exchange of information on the import and export of goods.</seg>
<seg id="54">3. Description of the state of value added tax and excise duties</seg>
<seg id="55">Value added tax</seg>
<seg id="56">Value added tax (hereinafter referred to as "VAT") was levied by financial or tax authorities on taxable transactions carried out domestically and by customs authorities on the importation of goods.</seg>
<seg id="57">Tax revenues for financial or tax authorities were determined by the difference between the collected own tax liability and the excess VAT deductions returned.</seg>
<seg id="58">The VAT revenues at the customs offices were due to the amount of tax collected by them.</seg>
<seg id="59">The tax collected by the customs authorities, in accordance with the basic principles of the VAT mechanism, was reflected in the tax deductions applied to financial or tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="60">For most financial or tax authorities, excess VAT deductions exceeded the tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="61">VAT is one of the core taxes in terms of state budget revenues, as it accounted for around 31% of the tax revenues of the state budget of the Czech Republic in 2003 and approximately 42% in the tax revenues of the state budget of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="62">The total VAT collection in the Czech Republic amounted to CZK 162.9 billion in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="63">The financial and customs authorities collected a total of CZK 394.3 billion in VAT in 2003 and the excess VAT deductions refunded totalled CZK 231.4 billion.</seg>
<seg id="64">Total VAT collection in the SR amounted to 83.8 billion Sk in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="65">Tax and customs authorities collected CZK 187.0 billion in VAT in 2003 and the excess VAT deductions refunded amounted to a total of EUR 103.2 billion.</seg>
<seg id="66">Excise taxes</seg>
<seg id="67">The collection of excise duties (hereinafter referred to as the SpD) was made by the relevant financial or tax authorities and on imports of products subject to SpD by the customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="68">SpD's share of state budget tax revenues in the Czech Republic was approximately 16% in 2003 and around 19% in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="69">The total collection of SpD collected in the Czech Republic by the financial and customs authorities in 2003 was CZK 85.6 billion and in the SR amounted to CZK 38.0 billion.</seg>
<seg id="70">4. The course of the inspection</seg>
<seg id="71">Cooperation between the SAO and the SAO of the SR took place in two stages.</seg>
<seg id="72">In the first stage a comparison of imports and exports of selected commodities from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia was carried out, in the second stage the results of this comparison were used in mutual verification of the implementation of selected commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and Slovakia and in checks carried out on the territory of both states.</seg>
<seg id="73">4.1.</seg>
<seg id="74">Preparing a control action</seg>
<seg id="75">The first proposal for cooperation in parallel VAT and SpD inspections was presented at a working meeting of representatives of the SAO and the SAO of the Slovak Republic in April 2003.</seg>
<seg id="76">In November 2003, a coordination meeting was held at which, inter alia, the selection of commodities - goods which represented a significant risk in complying with customs and tax legislation: - alcohol and spirits, tariff subheadings 2207 and 2208, - tobacco and tobacco products, tariff subheadings Nos.2401, 2402 and 2403, - computers and computer components, items and subheadings of customs tariff Nos 8471 and 8473 30, - mobile phones and their accessories, tariff subheadings Nos 8525 20 91, 8525 20 99, 8529 90 40.</seg>
<seg id="77">The two parties agreed that the selection of tax entities for inspection would be made: (a) from the unassigned items found by the comparison of exports and imports of selected commodities between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, (b) from entities carrying out imports and exports regularly or in one lump sum, (c) on the basis of the findings from the checks carried out by selected tax and tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="78">4.2. 4.2. Comparison of customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="79">In the first stage, a sample of imports and exports of selected commodities for the month of October 2002 tested a mechanism for the mutual allocation of JCD items registered in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="80">Subsequently, some exports from the Czech Republic were compared with imports into the Slovak Republic for 2002 and vice versa for selected commodities according to the customs tariff:</seg>
<seg id="81">- 2207 Undenatured ethyl alcohol with an alcoholic strength by volume of 80% vol. or more; ethyl alcohol and other spirits denatured, with any alcohol content,</seg>
<seg id="82">- 2208 Undenatured ethyl alcohol with an alcoholic strength by volume of less than 80% vol; spirits, liqueurs and other spirituous beverages;</seg>
<seg id="83">- 2401 Unprocessed tobacco; tobacco waste,</seg>
<seg id="84">- 2402 Cigars (whether or not cut off), cigarillos (cigarillos) and cigarettes from tobacco or tobacco substitutes,</seg>
<seg id="85">- 2403 Other tobacco products and tobacco substitutes; homogenised or reconstituted tobacco; tobacco extracts and punishments (essences),</seg>
<seg id="86">- 8525 20 91 Transmitting devices containing reception devices: For a cellular network (mobile phones),</seg>
<seg id="87">- 8525 20 99 Transmitting apparatus containing the receiving equipment: Other,</seg>
<seg id="88">- 8529 90 40 Parts suitable for use solely or principally with apparatus of headings 8525 to 8528.</seg>
<seg id="89">Other: Parts of apparatus falling within subheadings 8525 10 50, 8525 20 91, 8525 20 99, 8525 40 11 and 8527 90 92.</seg>
<seg id="90">JCD entries from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia were assigned to each other on the basis of the agreement of individual JCD paragraphs (e.g. invoiced price, quantity, weight, registration plate of the vehicle carrying cargo, date of crossing the national border, customs tariff item, etc.).</seg>
<seg id="91">The results of the comparison are presented in the following tables and charts.</seg>
<seg id="92">The mutual allocation of individual imports and exports was made more difficult, among other things, by the fact that commercial transactions were not declared in the same way on both sides.</seg>
<seg id="93">For example, exports from the Czech Republic declared on one export JCD were declared on several import JCDs in the territory of the Slovak Republic, or the export JCD had a different number of items from the import JCD.</seg>
<seg id="94">Other factors that influenced the success of the assignment were the different composition of the data in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia, as well as the time shift between the export records in the customs database of one country and the registration of corresponding imports in the customs database of the other country.</seg>
<seg id="95">The results of the comparison were used in the selection of control samples at the financial or tax authorities audited.</seg>
<seg id="96">Priority was chosen for some tax entities that made imports or exports between the Czech Republic and Slovakia, which could not be identified in both databases.</seg>
<seg id="97">Furthermore, some tax entities were selected for the verification of business transactions reported in VAT returns, for which data on imports or exports between the Czech Republic and Slovakia were found in both databases.</seg>
<seg id="98">4.3. Pilot control at the border customs crossing of Starý Hrozenkov-Drietoma</seg>
<seg id="99">The border customs crossing for the performance of pilot control was selected on the basis of a joint analysis of the unassigned JCD items in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="100">On the basis of a bilateral agreement between the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, the use of control sheets has been introduced at border customs crossings between the Czech Republic and Slovakia since 1.6.1998.</seg>
<seg id="101">The aim of this measure was to eliminate customs and tax evasion as far as possible, to ensure an overview of the movement of means of transport carrying goods of a commercial nature in the customs area and to create the conditions for mutual comparison of customs records.</seg>
<seg id="102">The joint pilot inspection was carried out on 8.3.2004 to 26.3.2004 and was aimed at examining this customs control system.</seg>
<seg id="103">Procedure for the use of control certificates at the Starý Hrozenkov-Drietoma border crossing:</seg>
<seg id="104">1) Consideration of the vehicle, issue of the inspection sheet and hand it over to the driver.</seg>
<seg id="105">2) Shutdown of the vehicle in the designated sector in the parking lot.</seg>
<seg id="106">Customs discussions in the check-in hall check-in hall of the Police of the Czech Republic, Police of the Slovak Republic, Customs Administration of the Czech Republic, Customs Administration of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="107">The execution of the check-in was confirmed by the individual components with a stamp on the checklist.</seg>
<seg id="108">3) Landing a vehicle into the area of carrying out a physical check.</seg>
<seg id="109">Presentation of the inspection sheet, JCD, or other documents to the customs officer - check the execution of all prescribed operations and documents.</seg>
<seg id="110">Performance of physical inspection by the relevant files.</seg>
<seg id="111">Removal of the vehicle from the customs area.</seg>
<seg id="112">Pozru: When goods were imported into the Czech Republic, the weighing of the vehicles were carried out directly by the staff of the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="113">When goods were imported into the SR, weighing vehicles were carried out by staff of a designated legal entity.</seg>
<seg id="114">The vehicles were registered in computer records after consideration.</seg>
<seg id="115">4.3.1 Control sample</seg>
<seg id="116">Exports from the Czech Republic to Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="117">The control sample was selected on the basis of an analysis of records from the customs database of exports of the Czech Republic in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="118">The composition of the control sample for exports is shown in Table 4.</seg>
<seg id="119">4.3.2. Check sheets and their records Exports from the Czech Republic to Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="120">When exported from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic, the inspection certificates were issued and registered by the SR Customs Administration.</seg>
<seg id="121">The Customs Administration of the Czech Republic recorded the registration numbers of these control sheets in the electronic database of exports.</seg>
<seg id="122">Of the number of 453 JCD items, the SAO supervised 256 cases of imports into the Slovak Republic according to data from the customs database of the Czech Republic and Slovakia. The remaining 197 JCD items were identified by the SAO of the SR in cooperation with the workers of the Drietoma border crossing.</seg>
<seg id="123">Exports from Slovakia to the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="124">When exported from Slovakia to the Czech Republic, the inspection certificates were issued and registered by the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="125">Out of a total of 339 JCD items of the selected SAO control sample in cooperation with the staff of the border customs crossing Starý Hrozenkov assigned to 295 JCD entries corresponding to the registration numbers of the control sheets.</seg>
<seg id="126">The remaining 44 cases were identified in their records by the workers of the border customs crossing of Drietoma and the export of goods from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic confirmed.</seg>
<seg id="127">The audit of the SAO and the SAO of the Slovak Republic did not detect deficiencies in the register of selected cases of imports and exports of goods in 2002 at the Starý Hrozenkov-Drietoma border crossing.</seg>
<seg id="128">4.4. Selected control findings when verifying commercial transactions</seg>
<seg id="129">Within the framework of international cooperation, the implementation of imports and exports between the Czech Republic and Slovakia was verified from the documents of customs administrations and financial and tax authorities on the territory of the other state.</seg>
<seg id="130">Selected tax entities have been verified:</seg>
<seg id="131">- whether the submitted JCD was registered in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia,</seg>
<seg id="132">- fulfilment of the legal conditions for the application of the VAT deduction on importation, the refund of excess VAT deduction and the application of the VAT exemption on export.</seg>
<seg id="133">The verification of commercial transactions was found to be:</seg>
<seg id="134">1. The SAO SR asked for verification of the implementation of alcohol exports at a statistical value of 56 989 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="135">The SAO identified corresponding imports in the customs database of the Czech Republic in a statistical value of CZK 42,624.</seg>
<seg id="136">2. The company involved in the import and export of photographic equipment and accessories applied an excess VAT deduction of CZK 3,740,664 in the VAT return for the month of December 2002.</seg>
<seg id="137">In order to control reported exports from the Czech Republic, the SAO selected 3 JCD (16 items) with a statistical value of CZK 1,274,822.</seg>
<seg id="138">The SAO of the SR identified 3 corresponding import JCD (17 items) in a statistical value of 1 724 321 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="139">VAT was paid to the competent customs office in the SR.</seg>
<seg id="140">3. The company, whose business was mainly the trade in optical devices, applied a total excess VAT deduction in 2002 of CZK 4 1 36 000 higher than the tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="141">To verify the reported business activity, the SAO selected an export JCD (32 items) with a statistical value of CZK 7,154,124.</seg>
<seg id="142">The SAO of the SR found that this JCD corresponds to the import JCD (12 headings) with a statistical value of 9 653 827 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="143">VAT was paid to the competent customs office in the SR.</seg>
<seg id="144">4. The company engaged in, inter alia, buying goods for resale and sale, did not report any exports of goods in the submitted VAT returns in 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="145">According to the customs database of the Czech Republic, the statistical value of exports of goods in 2002 totalled CZK 3,439,888.</seg>
<seg id="146">Based on these facts, the SAO selected 5 export JCDs (5 items) for verification with a total statistical value of CZK 669,839.</seg>
<seg id="147">The SAO of the SR identified 5 corresponding import JCDs (5 items) in a statistical value of 1 012 656 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="148">The audit of the SAO of the SR at the relevant tax office proved the implementation of the declared imports and the payment of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="149">5. The company whose business was, among other things, the purchase of goods for resale and sale, production, installation and repair of electrical machinery and appliances, reported in 2002 the export of goods worth CZK 12,966,706 in VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="150">According to the customs database of the Czech Republic, in 2002 the total value of exports was CZK 14,474,381.</seg>
<seg id="151">The SAO submitted 17 export JCDs (59 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 2,975,122.</seg>
<seg id="152">The SAO identified SR 13 JCD (50 items) in the SR customs database with a statistical value of 3,621,370 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="153">In the SR customs database it was not possible to identify the corresponding import JCD to 4 export JCD (9 items) with a total statistical value of 399 776 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="154">The competent tax authority in the Slovak Republic verified these imports from the taxpayer.</seg>
<seg id="155">The tax entity, listed on the JCD as an importer in the Slovak Republic, commented in the minutes of the local investigation that it had not implemented the imports declared on Czech export JCDs.</seg>
<seg id="156">The SAO of SR therefore asked the local competent tax authority to carry out a tax audit of VAT and corporate income tax for the 2002 and 2003 tax.</seg>
<seg id="157">6. The company involved in importing and selling cigarettes exported tobacco stickers in a statistical value of CZK 7,338,199 according to the Czech customs database in 2002 and a statistical value of CZK 12,228,545 in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="158">In the VAT tax returns, the company did not report any exports in 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="159">The SAO selected 5 export JCDs (5 items) for verification with a total statistical value of CZK 2,471,598.</seg>
<seg id="160">To 4 export JCD (4 items) with a total statistical value of 2,246,860 CZK, the SAO identified SR 7 JCD (7 items) in the customs database SR 7 JCD (7 items) in the statistical value of 2,919,514 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="161">The export JCD (1 item) with a statistical value of CZK 224,738 could not be assigned adequate imports in the SR customs database.</seg>
<seg id="162">7. The software company did not report exports of goods in the VAT returns for 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="163">According to the customs database of the Czech Republic, the statistical value of exports of goods in 2002 and 2003 totalled CZK 1,630 198.</seg>
<seg id="164">The SAO selected for verification in SR 9 JCD (9 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 755,588.</seg>
<seg id="165">In the customs database of the SR SAO SR identified 8 JCD (8 items) in the statistical value of 915 601 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="166">The export JCD (1 entry) with a statistical value of CZK 68,286 could not be attributed to the corresponding imports in the SR customs database.</seg>
<seg id="167">In these cases, it was not possible to identify in the SR customs database corresponding to imports to 6 JCDs with a statistical value of CZK 692,800.</seg>
<seg id="168">Of which:</seg>
<seg id="169">- to 2 export JCDs from the customs database of the Czech Republic with a statistical value of CZK 293,024, the corresponding import JCD could not be identified in the SR customs database (see paragraphs 6 and 7).</seg>
<seg id="170">Due to a certain error rate in entering data into the customs database, it was not possible to identify some registered imports, e.g. in cases where the name of the importer was missing or there was an error in the tax identification number (hereinafter referred to as the "DIČ").</seg>
<seg id="171">It is therefore not possible to conclude with certainty that those exports did not materialise.</seg>
<seg id="172">- for 4 export JCDs from the customs database of the Czech Republic, imports corresponding to exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic with a statistical value of 399 776 CZK have not been demonstrated (see paragraph 5).</seg>
<seg id="173">In such cases, suspicion of a fictitious export of goods for the purpose of unauthorised application of the VAT deduction is justified.</seg>
<seg id="174">5. Control of imports and exports of goods and services as part of the control of selected financial or tax authorities</seg>
<seg id="175">5.1. Control sample</seg>
<seg id="176">In order to verify the fulfilment of the obligations of tax entities in the import and export of goods and services, and to evaluate the level of cooperation between the financial and customs authorities, the files of the tax authorities were selected on the audited financial or tax authorities according to the following criteria:</seg>
<seg id="177">1. tax entities were selected from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia: (a) with the highest volume of imports, (b) with the highest amount of VAT charged, (c) with the highest volume of exports,</seg>
<seg id="178">2. from the registration of financial or tax authorities were selected tax entities according to the above: (a) applied VAT deductions on importation, (b) excess VAT deductions applied, (c) entitlement to a refund of SpD, (d) the VAT exemption claimed on export,</seg>
<seg id="179">3. tax entities for which tax control has been carried out.</seg>
<seg id="180">Sampling was made regardless of the country of destination with a focus on risky commodities.</seg>
<seg id="181">5.2. Control findings in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="182">An overview of imports into the Czech Republic and exports from the Czech Republic for risky commodities in 2002 and 2003 is shown in the following table:</seg>
<seg id="183">5.2.1. Check of the selected sample at the tax authorities</seg>
<seg id="184">The SAO focused mainly on the audited tax authorities:</seg>
<seg id="185">- the procedure of the tax authorities in verifying the correctness of the declared VAT,</seg>
<seg id="186">- the cooperation of the tax authorities with the customs administration,</seg>
<seg id="187">- comparing the data from the customs database with the JCD database at the tax authorities with a focus on comparing the declared value, applying the correct VAT rate following the customs classification of goods or services, or comparing the data on the JCD and the accompanying invoices with the particulars in the customs database,</seg>
<seg id="188">- Comparison of VAT return data on transactions made and received from abroad with data in the JCD database at the tax authorities or in the customs database,</seg>
<seg id="189">- how to verify the right to VAT exemption when exporting goods or services abroad,</seg>
<seg id="190">- a comparison of the volume of exports of goods or services declared in VAT tax returns with data from the customs database.</seg>
<seg id="191">The JCD database at the tax authorities contained only records of those imports and exports for which tax entities were required to include imports or exports in the tax return.</seg>
<seg id="192">The audited tax authorities examined the files of the tax entities, which reported in VAT returns in 2002 and 2003 imports totalling CZK 60,396,379,000 and the corresponding VAT totalling CZK 12,644,052.</seg>
<seg id="193">Furthermore, the files of the tax entities reporting in tax returns for the years 2002 and 2003 were checked with exports totalling CZK 47,323,111,000.</seg>
<seg id="194">According to the Czech Republic's customs database, tax entities for which imports and exports were examined between the Czech Republic and Slovakia, carried out imports into the Czech Republic from Slovakia in 2002 and 2003 with a total VAT base of CZK 3,759,352,000, VAT amounting to CZK 767,607,000 and exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic with a total statistical value of CZK 1,989,090,000.</seg>
<seg id="195">The identified differences between the records in the JCD database at the tax authorities and in the customs database of the Czech Republic were examined as follows:</seg>
<seg id="196">- JCD items that were missing from the customs database of the Czech Republic were requested directly at the General Directorate of Customs of the Czech Republic,</seg>
<seg id="197">- for JCD items missing from the database of tax authorities, it has been verified that these are not cancelled documents,</seg>
<seg id="198">- for JCD items for which different values were found between the customs database of the Czech Republic and the database of the tax authorities, the relevant JCDs were requested at the General Directorate of Customs of the Czech Republic in written form, including the attached invoices.</seg>
<seg id="199">The screening revealed that the JCD database at the tax authorities did not include, for example, records of import JCDs with a total VAT value of CZK 3,622,000 and records of export JCDs with a total statistical value of CZK 9,359,000.</seg>
<seg id="200">5.2.1.1. Detected differences</seg>
<seg id="201">By comparing the JCD database at the tax authorities and the cumulated tax liability for 2002 and 2003 in the VAT returns for the selected sample of tax entities, the following differences were found:</seg>
<seg id="202">Differences in values were mainly due to:</seg>
<seg id="203">- The time shift between the realisation of imports and the exercise of the right to deduct VAT charged on the importation of goods.</seg>
<seg id="204">The taxpayer was entitled to deduct the tax on the importation of goods within 3 years of the end of the tax year during which the goods were placed under the relevant scheme or, in the case of the temporary admission procedure, no later than 3 years after the end of the tax period during which the scheme was terminated.</seg>
<seg id="205">- The time difference between the realisation of exports and the moment when the taxpayer received JCD.</seg>
<seg id="206">The taxpayer was obliged to provide data on realized exports exempt from the obligation to apply output tax to the VAT return at the earliest for the tax period in which the goods came out of the country if they simultaneously had a tax document, which was JCD.</seg>
<seg id="207">- Failure to comply with the obligations of tax entities when reporting imports and exports in VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="208">In some cases, tax entities did not include correct data on imports and exports in VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="209">Since tax entities did not have to attach JCD lists to the VAT return filed, it has been made more difficult to control the right to deduct VAT or VAT exemption by the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="210">5.2.2.2. Synergies between the financial and customs authorities</seg>
<seg id="211">During the audited period, following a decision by the customs authorities, import or export duties and VAT were refunded or remitted.</seg>
<seg id="212">Tax entities were required by law to reduce the previously exercised right to deduct VAT by the amount of tax returned by the customs office, in a tax return for the period in which the tax was returned.</seg>
<seg id="213">No legislation provided for the transmission of information on changes in the amount of customs duties and VAT from customs offices to the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="214">Some audited tax authorities received this information, but irregularly or with considerable delay and only from some customs offices.</seg>
<seg id="215">One audited tax office did not receive this information at all.</seg>
<seg id="216">If the tax office did not receive information on changes in the amount of duty and VAT directly from the customs office, it did not have the information necessary to check compliance with the legal obligation of tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="217">In 2002, customs authorities refunded VAT of more than EUR 319 million. CZK and in 2003 in the amount of over 398 mil. CZK.</seg>
<seg id="218">The results of the audit pointed to persistent shortcomings in the activities of tax authorities, some systemic errors in the cooperation of the tax authorities with the customs authorities and the failure of certain obligations of VAT and SpD payers.</seg>
<seg id="219">In the administration of VAT and SpD, weaknesses were identified in particular in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="220">(a) on the abolition of VAT registrations, the fulfilment of the obligation on payers to pay VAT on the registered assets, or which should have been registered on the date of cancellation of the registration in respect of which the payer applied the deduction, verified only rarely,</seg>
<seg id="221">(b) the tax authorities have not consistently used the possibility of carrying out a tax audit or local investigation.</seg>
<seg id="222">In this case, in some cases, there was a lack of verification of the right to deduct VAT,</seg>
<seg id="223">(c) the official records and reports on the oral hearing did not contain all the necessary data demonstrating the legitimacy of the excess VAT deductions applied,</seg>
<seg id="224">(d) the tax authorities did not sufficiently verify the imports and exports reported in VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="225">5.3. Control findings in SR</seg>
<seg id="226">5.3.1. Check of selected sample at tax offices</seg>
<seg id="227">For the selected sample of the SAO SR, it verified or the tax office carried out a tax audit for the tax years 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="228">After analysing the filed tax returns and refund requests from selected tax entities of the SAO SR, the tax office asked for the provision of the relevant JCDs documenting imports and exports, invoices and proofs of payment of the tax.</seg>
<seg id="229">Subsequently, the SAO of the Slovak Republic checked that the submitted JCD was registered in the customs database of imports and exports and the fulfilment of decisive facts and legal conditions when applying the deduction of input tax by way of importation, when the excess VAT deduction was refunded, the application of the exemption in respect of exports and the refund of SpD.</seg>
<seg id="230">In 10 audited tax offices, the SAO of the Slovak Republic verified selected cases of imports and exports of goods between the Slovak Republic in the structure according to the respect of JCD items and the sum of the statistical values given in the following table.</seg>
<seg id="231">In total, imports were checked at a statistical value of CZK 856.2 million. Sk, which represents 5.11% of the total value of imports of selected commodities from the Czech Republic into SROV.</seg>
<seg id="232">Exports of selected commodities were checked at a total statistical value of 176 million. Sk, which from the total value of exports of selected commodities from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic represents 6.87%.</seg>
<seg id="233">In addition, 618 cases of imports of additional goods and services (mainly white technology, packaging and software) from EU countries were checked into the Slovak Republic with a total statistical value of CZK 532.8 million. Sk.</seg>
<seg id="234">5.3.2. Synergies between tax and customs authorities</seg>
<seg id="235">The SAO OF THE SR's audit found discrepancies between the data registered in the SR customs database and the data reported in specific VAT returns, e.g.:</seg>
<seg id="236">- 2 tax entities (natural persons) reported in tax returns imports of goods with a total value of 1 589 261 Sk, on the basis of which they claimed a refund of excess VAT deductions.</seg>
<seg id="237">In local investigations carried out at the instigation of the SAO OF THE SR, tax entities were unable to prove to the tax authority the legitimacy of the application of input tax with the relevant documents on the implementation of imports and the payment of VAT,</seg>
<seg id="238">- In the tax return for the January 2003 tax year, the taxpayer declared the taxable transaction received at the value of 77 167 576 Sk, the export of goods worth 18 006 041 Sk and claimed an excess VAT deduction of 17 157 101 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="239">VAT returns filed for 2003 show that the difference between the volume of purchases and exports of 59 161 535 Sk, which arose in January 2003, was not settled throughout 2003.</seg>
<seg id="240">In the above cases, the SAO SR asked the relevant tax authorities to carry out a tax audit of the excess VAT deductions applied.</seg>
<seg id="241">- in another case, the tax entity (s.r.o.) for the January to June 2002 tax year declared in VAT returns the export of goods with a total value of 87 199 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="242">By verification in the SR customs database, it was found that the taxpayer made exports at a statistical value of 296 747 Sk during that period.</seg>
<seg id="243">The tax office carried out a local investigation multiple times at the company's headquarters, finding that the company's managing director (UK citizen) had travelled and the company had left the leased premises without terminating the lease in August 2002.</seg>
<seg id="244">At the time of the SAO's audit of the SR SAO, the tax administrator filed a complaint with the law enforcement authorities on suspicion of committing the crime of non-taxation.</seg>
<seg id="245">Based on the results of the audit at selected tax offices, the SAO of the SR notes that the biggest problems in the performance of the administration and control of VAT and SpD occurred mainly in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="246">- non-use of the possibility of carrying out VAT control on problematic tax entities, in particular in cases of high value of excess VAT deductions;</seg>
<seg id="247">- the tax inspection protocols did not contain an inventory of the documents audited</seg>
<seg id="248">- JCD on the import and export of goods,</seg>
<seg id="249">- insufficient screening of reported imports and exports of goods in tax returns,</seg>
<seg id="250">- lengthy management of tax administrators in issuing decisions, in particular in the context of the assessment procedure, even as a result of the termination of the right to impose penalties;</seg>
<seg id="251">- non-compliance with legal conditions when granting tax deferrals;</seg>
<seg id="252">- non-compensation of VAT arrears within the deadline for the refund of excess VAT deduction,</seg>
<seg id="253">- insufficient use of all forms of security and recovery of tax arrears.</seg>
<seg id="254">On the basis of the SAO's examination of the findings, the SR asked the relevant tax authorities to carry out a VAT check with a focus on the legitimacy of the excess VAT deductions applied for 14 tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="255">Measures have been taken at all audited tax offices to remedy the identified deficiencies, the implementation of which will be monitored and monitored by the SAO of the SR.</seg>
<seg id="256">6. Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="257">International cooperation has made it possible to examine trade transactions carried out between trading partners from both states and pointed to shortcomings in the import and export records.</seg>
<seg id="258">The results of the checks also identified persistent shortcomings in the fulfilment of VAT and SpD obligations, in the activities of financial or tax authorities, in the system of cooperation and exchange of information between tax authorities and customs administrations, which ultimately reduced the efficiency and effectiveness of tax controls.</seg>
<seg id="259">The lessons learned also showed that the tax authorities in the Czech Republic have basic data on imports and exports from the Czech customs database within the tax information system. There is no similar system for transmitting information on imports and exports of goods between customs and tax administrations in the SR.</seg>
<seg id="260">The procedure for verifying the performance of the VAT and SpD management was not the same, given the different rules and conditions in the territory of the two States.</seg>
<seg id="261">The SAO verified the necessary data from information obtained from the customs administration of the Czech Republic and from the documents available at the audited tax offices. The SAO of SR verified the execution of commercial transactions from documents of tax entities requested through tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="262">If irregularities were found, he asked the tax authorities to carry out tax inspections.</seg>
<seg id="263">The parallel VAT and SpD checks carried out assessed the state of administration of these taxes in the period prior to joining the European Union and pointed to the need for further cooperation in this area.</seg>
<seg id="264">Mutual cooperation will further deepen in the control of the activities of financial or tax authorities in connection with the adoption of the new VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="265">One of the new obligations related to the delivery of goods to other Member States of the European Union is the submission of a so-called recapitulative statement.</seg>
<seg id="266">This report must be made by all VAT payers who have made the supply of goods to another Member State to a person registered for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="267">Tax administrators are required to enter data from recapitulative statements into the VIES (VAT Information Exchange System) to which tax administrations from the Member States of the European Union have access.</seg>
<seg id="268">Financial or tax authorities then have the possibility to compare these data with the data contained in the filed VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="269">This system is further used to verify the validity of the VAT number of persons registered for VAT, to verify the validity of the VAT exemption applied on the supply of goods to another Member State and to check the proper taxation of goods.</seg>
<seg id="270">The implementation of parallel control actions showed the possibilities of cooperation between the SAO and the SAO SR.</seg>
<seg id="271">The results of these control actions will be confronted with the outputs of upcoming control actions, which will, among other things, focus on examining the VIES system, which is intended to prevent tax evasion in so-called "intra-community supplies."</seg>
<seg id="272">Given the importance of VAT and SpD for budget revenues, control action needs to be focused primarily on monitoring and identifying risky areas in order to limit the scope for tax evasion to indirect taxes.</seg>
<seg id="273">Communications</seg>
<seg id="274">This report was prepared in Czech, English and Slovak and signed by the Vice-President of the Supreme Audit Office and the chairman of Najýššie's control department of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
</p>
