<doc docid="testsuite-segment_65-KA_04_23" genre="news" origlang="cs" sysid="uedin-uedin-transformer-base.snapshot.after-65K-updates">
<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the results of the inspection at asylum facilities in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">State property and funds earmarked for securing the activities of the Administration of Refugee Facilities of the Ministry of the Interior</seg>
<seg id="3">Audit Action No 04/23 "Property of the State and funds earmarked for securing the activities of the Administration of Refugee Facilities of the Ministry of the Interior"</seg>
<seg id="4">Audit Action No 15/2004 "Control of pubs with the assets of the staff and financial prostheses intended for the provision of asylum and temporary attacking cudzincom in SR"</seg>
<seg id="5">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="6">Population migration is one of the phenomena that has a global character and has become an inseparable part of the current development stage of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="7">Its cause is, in particular, the flight of citizens from their country of origin or last residency from persecution, in particular for reasons of racial, religious, national, political, as well as the consequences of military conflicts and ethnic cleansing.</seg>
<seg id="8">Their aim is to gain asylum and integrate into society, especially in some of Europe's developed democratic countries.</seg>
<seg id="9">A large group is also made up of foreigners, whose reason for migration is unfavourable economic and living conditions.</seg>
<seg id="10">Migration is not a new phenomenon.</seg>
<seg id="11">The setting of concrete principles for aid to refugees has already been brought about by the adoption of the 1951 Geneva Agreement and the 1967 New York Protocol on the status of refugees, the acceptance of which the governments of the signatory countries have pledged to apply them in their foreign-policy orientation.</seg>
<seg id="12">The Czech and Slovak Federative Republic ratified the New York Protocol in 1991 and the Geneva Agreement in 1992.</seg>
<seg id="13">After the split in 1993, both the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic declared their position on the refugee issue by continuing to implement adopted international documents and confirmed their binding nature within the framework of national legislation by a legal act.</seg>
<seg id="14">Both republics have also enshrined the granting of asylum in their constitutional laws.</seg>
<seg id="15">The asylum process and related issues were targeted parallel checks carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Najýš Control Office of the Slovak Republic, the results of which are contained in a joint final report.</seg>
<seg id="16">Cooperation between the highest control authorities of both countries was implemented on the basis of the "Contract of Cooperation in Control Activities" (hereinafter referred to as the Treaty") concluded in April 2004.</seg>
<seg id="17">The two Parties undertook to provide each other with information in the Treaty on the legislation governing the asylum procedure in the State of the other Contracting Party, selected statistical data on the number of asylum seekers and the results of the asylum process, as well as information on asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="18">The aim of the parallel control action was to set out the same problem areas and to highlight the consequences of this for the area of population migration.</seg>
<seg id="19">Cooperation consisted in the harmonisation of the control action programme, the exchange of information to the extent provided for by the Treaty and the drawing up of a joint final report on the outcome of the checks.</seg>
<seg id="20">The first joint meeting, which took place from 5.4. to 7.4.2004, set out the same headings of the audited issue and control procedures for the preparation of control actions.</seg>
<seg id="21">At the second meeting, which took place on 28.6. to 30.6.2004, the common points for the control action programme were specified.</seg>
<seg id="22">During the third joint meeting, which took place during the audit operation on 8.11. to 10.11.2004, there was an exchange of experience from the ongoing inspections.</seg>
<seg id="23">The forms of outputs from the checks were specified and the structure and content of the joint final report drawn up from 14.2. to 17.2. 2005 at the last joint meeting were set out.</seg>
<seg id="24">The checks were carried out in parallel between September 2004 and January 2005.</seg>
<seg id="25">In the Czech Republic, the inspection was carried out by auditors of the Department of Defence and Security and selected territorial unions.</seg>
<seg id="26">The audited bodies were the Ministry of the Interior (hereinafter referred to as "MV") and the Administration of Refugee Facilities of the Ministry of the Interior (hereinafter referred to as "SUZ").</seg>
<seg id="27">In the Slovak Republic, the defence section, vnútra and the staff of the úradov carried out a check.</seg>
<seg id="28">The audited entity was the Migration Department of the Ministry of Slovakia (hereinafter referred to as "MÚ").</seg>
<seg id="29">The audited period was 2001, 2002, 2003 (the period checked).</seg>
<seg id="30">In some cases, statistical data over a longer period of time are also used in the joint report.</seg>
<seg id="31">2. Recapitulation of control results</seg>
<seg id="32">2.1. 2.1. Assessment of control activity</seg>
<seg id="33">The subject of parallel checks was: - asylum process, - asylum facilities, - management of funds and state property, - internal control system.</seg>
<seg id="34">The mutual exchange of experience gained between the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Najýš Control Office of the Slovak Republic took place at the stage of preparation and implementation of control actions.</seg>
<seg id="35">This exchange made it possible to evaluate the supporting documents submitted more thoroughly, to analyse the causes of the identified differences in the safeguarding of the asylum process.</seg>
<seg id="36">This made it possible to focus on the decisive problems affecting the activities of asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="37">Ultimately, this positively affected the quality of carrying out the control activity.</seg>
<seg id="38">2.2 Summary of the results of the inspection</seg>
<seg id="39">The harmonisation of the asylum law of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic with European Union documents (EU) has been the subject of evaluation reports by the European Commission on the readiness of both countries to join the EU.</seg>
<seg id="40">The adoption of legislation governing this area continues after the accession of both countries to the EU in order to further align with EU law.</seg>
<seg id="41">The number of asylum seekers in the Czech Republic increased significantly in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="42">In the Slovak Republic, the number of applicants has a steadily growing trend, with a significant increase in applicants in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="43">Within the meaning of international agreements, the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic provide financial and material security to asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="44">The state budget of both countries earmarks the necessary funds for this purpose.</seg>
<seg id="45">The amount of expenditure drawn from the state budget of both countries is influenced in particular by the number of applicants, the duration of the asylum procedure until granting or not granting asylum, as well as the health of applicants.</seg>
<seg id="46">The amount of some selected benefits is comparable in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="47">The Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic set up asylum facilities in which they gradually created suitable conditions for the stay of participants in the asylum procedure.</seg>
<seg id="48">During the stay, asylum seekers are provided with accommodation, catering, health care and basic material equipment and sanitary items.</seg>
<seg id="49">At the same time, courses are organised as part of leisure activities and applicants are created the conditions for cultural and sporting activities.</seg>
<seg id="50">Asylum facilities include reception centres and residential centres, in the Czech Republic as well as integration centres.</seg>
<seg id="51">The cost of one residential day depends on the occupancy and equipment of the Centre and is comparable in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="52">In the Czech Republic, the capacity of asylum facilities is basically stabilised.</seg>
<seg id="53">In the Slovak Republic, it is projected to increase by almost 1,000 seats in the next two years.</seg>
<seg id="54">The aim is to create the conditions for applicants, whose growing number is expected to continue in the coming years in the context of the application of the Dublin Convention.</seg>
<seg id="55">In the Czech Republic, the highest part of the approved budget expenditure was spent on securing services. The decisive expenditure of this item was the expenditure on the accommodation and catering of applicants in asylum facilities operated under the contract, the healthcare expenditure provided to asylum seekers and the costs of a permanent security service ensuring the protection of asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="56">A significant part of the total expenditure was also spent on salaries, payments for work carried out and premiums.</seg>
<seg id="57">In the Slovak Republic, the budgetary management of the security of migration policy and the asylum process was marked by many budgetary measures that addressed legitimate requirements related to the increase in the number of asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="58">Current expenditure was a decisive factor in the execution of current expenditure on wages, salaries and premiums, expenditure on materials and services and expenditure on security services.</seg>
<seg id="59">The results of the audit in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic highlighted some similar shortcomings that did not have a major impact on the financial management and management of the state's property.</seg>
<seg id="60">These were shortcomings, in particular, in the area of the use of state budget funds in breach of the purpose for which they were determined by the State Budget Act, when ordinary expenditure was covered by actions having the character of a technical appreciation of fixed tangible assets.</seg>
<seg id="61">The Accounting Act in the field of inventory and non-compliance with the accounting curriculum was also violated.</seg>
<seg id="62">In the Czech Republic, minor deficiencies were also found in the disposal of state property when it was left to use another person without a contract.</seg>
<seg id="63">Failure to comply with the deadline for reporting changes to the Land Registry data violated the Land Registry Act and leaving the waste for disposal to a person who was not a person authorized for waste management was violated by the Waste Act.</seg>
<seg id="64">In the Slovak Republic, shortcomings were also found in the provision of disproportionately high advances for electricity and natural gas abstraction, shortcomings in public procurement and the management of state property when it was not sufficiently secured by its registration and the method of liquidation of unnecessary assets was not proven.</seg>
<seg id="65">The internal control system has been secured in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic within the meaning of the generally binding legislation in force governing the way financial control is carried out.</seg>
<seg id="66">No deficiencies were found in the written documentation submitted.</seg>
<seg id="67">Despite some identified shortcomings, the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and Najvyšší control úrad of the Slovak Republic, evaluate positively the procedure of SUZ and the Municipality in the provision of services for asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="68">Based on the lessons learned during the inspection, the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Najvyšší Control Office of the Slovak Republic note that despite a significant increase in the number of asylum seekers in recent years, the relevant organisational units of both countries have managed tasks related to the care of asylum seekers at an appropriate level.</seg>
<seg id="69">The evaluation shows that the system is functional and stable.</seg>
<seg id="70">The results of the inspection were discussed with interested statutory representatives of the respective organizational units of the state on the Czech and Slovak sides.</seg>
<seg id="71">Based on the results of the audit, we recommend that the positive methodological experience of the audit be used in other joint control actions in the framework of international cooperation of supreme audit institutions.</seg>
<seg id="72">3. Legislative framework</seg>
<seg id="73">In both the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, asylum law is based on the 1951 Geneva Convention (Convention on the Status of Refugees and the Secondary New York Protocol of 1967).</seg>
<seg id="74">The first legislation was implemented by Act No. 498/1990 Coll., on Refugees.</seg>
<seg id="75">Act No. 325/1999 Coll., on Asylum and on Amendments to Act No. 83/1991 Coll., on the Police of the Czech Republic, has been effective in the Czech Republic since 1 January 2000.</seg>
<seg id="76">This Act has been amended a total of five times (Act No. 2/2002 Coll., Act No. 217/2002 Coll., Act No. 320/2002 Coll., Act No. 519/2002 Coll. and Act No. 222/2003 Coll.).</seg>
<seg id="77">Two other amendments to Act No. 325/1999 Coll., on Asylum, are currently in the legislative process, and the adoption of further amendments will be tied to European legislation.</seg>
<seg id="78">At the time of the creation of Act No. 325/1999 Coll., on Asylum, the area of asylum was part of the 3rd pillar of the EU and asylum documents were in terms of binding political documents.</seg>
