<seg id="1">Joint report on parallel expenditure controls on the construction of the motorway Prague – Dresden</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">Without the existence of trans-European transport networks, a modern, dynamic and, above all, united Europe would be difficult to imagine.</seg>
<seg id="4">Quality transport networks are a prerequisite for maintaining and raising the standard of living of Europeans.</seg>
<seg id="5">Creating conditions for fast, safe, reliable and cheap transport of people and costs is an important task for the state administration.</seg>
<seg id="6">It is a very demanding task both in organizational and technical terms and financially.</seg>
<seg id="7">European efforts at sustainable mobility often and hard to find compromises with Europe's interest in maintaining a healthy and human-friendly environment.</seg>
<seg id="8">Construction of transport infrastructure, also thanks to the necessary measures in favour of the environment, are financially challenging.</seg>
<seg id="9">Considerated procedures and decisions of the state administration in the preparation and acquisition of transport constructions can bring significant savings from public financial resources that can be used differently for the benefit of citizens.</seg>
<seg id="10">One of the roles of the audit institutions is to actively seek out shortcomings that have led to less than achievable cost-effectiveness, efficiency and effectiveness of expenditure on transport infrastructure construction.</seg>
<seg id="11">The audit institutions should not only alert the state administration to the shortcomings identified, but recommend measures that lead to an improvement in the situation, for the benefit of the citizens, for the benefit of Europe.</seg>
<seg id="12">Short summary</seg>
<seg id="13">The two highest audit institutions of the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as Germany and the Czech Republic) were carried out by the Bundesrechnungshof (BRH) and the Supreme Audit Office (SAO) in 2005 and 2006 parallel inspections of expenditure on the construction of the motorway Prague – Dresden (distance D 8 in the Czech Republic and motorway A 17 in Germany).</seg>
<seg id="14">The highways are connected by a border bridge co-financed by both countries.</seg>
<seg id="15">Thanks to cooperation with the SAO, BRH was able to carry out a thorough check on the efficiency of the funds spent on the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="16">On the basis of close cooperation with BRH, the SAO obtained the necessary data on the amount of German bridge and tunnel costs for comparative purposes.</seg>
<seg id="17">The Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany concluded a contract for the construction of a border bridge in 2000.</seg>
<seg id="18">According to the construction process, the completion date was eventually scheduled for the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">During the award of the contract, however, the Road and Motorway Directorate of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the RMD) made mistakes that led to an extension of the duration of the competition and the reduction of the construction time.</seg>
<seg id="20">The contract with the contractor was thus signed later than anticipated.</seg>
<seg id="21">The contractor agreed to build the bridge in a shorter time and ensure its completion in 2006.</seg>
<seg id="22">As a result, however, the RMD had to accept a significant increase in the price of the bridge.</seg>
<seg id="23">As part of the joint inspection work, the prices of bridges on motorways D 8 and A 17 were compared on the basis of the conversion into m2 of the bridge structure area.</seg>
<seg id="24">The statistical analysis of prices made it possible to identify bridges with high costs per m2 area.</seg>
<seg id="25">Analysis revealed that the border bridge was the most expensive bridge in a group of large bridges with a length of over 100 metres.</seg>
<seg id="26">The price increase could also be attributed to the delay that occurred during the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="27">When analysing the cost of building the tunnels, inspectors found that the prices of tunnels on the D 8 motorway were significantly higher than those of comparable tunnels in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="28">BRH and the SAO now have a database of the prices of bridges and tunnels, on which they will be able to rely on for future checks on the effectiveness of the means used for transport infrastructure purposes.</seg>
<seg id="29">For the construction of bridges, both control institutions recommend: standardization of bridge structures and the use of coupled steel-concrete and special structures only in cases where prestressed reinforced concrete bridges are not adequate.</seg>
<seg id="30">One of the main hallmarks of the collaboration was her team spirit and informality.</seg>
<seg id="31">During the parallel control, the auditors were involved in their specific knowledge and skills.</seg>
<seg id="32">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="33">This report reports on the progress and results of parallel checks on funds spent on the construction of the motorway connecting Dresden and Prague (D 8 in the Czech Republic and A 17 in Germany).</seg>
<seg id="34">The checks focused on the economy, efficiency and effectiveness of the expenditure incurred.</seg>
<seg id="35">Parallel checks were carried out by BRH in Germany and the SAO in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="36">Parallel checks took place in 2005 and 2006.</seg>
<seg id="37">The SAO audited the economy, efficiency and effectiveness of spending of approximately CZK 20 billion including VAT (approximately €690 million) for the border section of the D 8 motorway, which has the figure 0807.</seg>
<seg id="38">Of this amount, €64 million from European funds (ISPA) was planned to be used.</seg>
<seg id="39">In addition to the parallel control carried out jointly with the SAO, BRH controlled the preparation and construction of the A 17 motorway in 2003 and 2005.</seg>
<seg id="40">The funds spent on the construction of all three sections of the A 17 motorway amounted to around €670 million, of which €277 million will be co-financed by European funds (EFRE).</seg>
<seg id="41">The highway from Prague to Dresden is part of the Trans-European Transport Corridor IV. Dresden – central and southern parts of Eastern Europe – Istanbul.</seg>
<seg id="42">The D 8 motorway runs from Prague through Ústí nad Labem to the state border.</seg>
<seg id="43">Highway A 17 runs from the state border of the Czech Republic/Germany to Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="44">At the time of the inspection, border sections of both motorways were under construction.</seg>
<seg id="45">These sections were put into operation on 21 December 2006.</seg>
<seg id="46">On the German side, the motorway is completed all the way to Dresden, while it is not finished on the Czech side of the D 8 motorway, because the section no. 0805 of 16.4 km through the Bohemian Central Mountains between Řehlovice and Lovosice is still in the preparatory phase.</seg>
<seg id="47">According to the plan, section No 0805 between Prague and Ústí nad Labem is to pass through the protected landscape area of the Czech Central Mountains.</seg>
<seg id="48">According to forecasts made in the Czech Republic in 2001, there should be an operating intensity of 22,940 vehicles per day in 2008 on the border section No 0807 of the D 8 motorway.</seg>
<seg id="49">According to German forecasts, the traffic intensity at the Czech border will total about 25,000 vehicles per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="50">In 2000, Germany and the Czech Republic concluded the Treaty between the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic on the interconnection of the German motorway A 17 and the Czech motorway D 8 on the common state border by building a border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="51">Both states are involved in the construction of the bridge, so the inspection of the construction of this bridge was an important aspect of the parallel checks carried out by the two inspection institutions.</seg>
<seg id="52">BRH and SAO cooperation</seg>
<seg id="53">Since mid-2005, the two highest audit institutions have discussed close cooperation in controlling the construction of the motorway connecting Prague and Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="54">The two sides had serious reasons for such cooperation:</seg>
<seg id="55">1.</seg>
<seg id="56">Germany is financially involved in the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="57">Its planning and construction rests with the RMD.</seg>
<seg id="58">Therefore, BRH itself did not have the opportunity to carry out a check of this construction project.</seg>
<seg id="59">2.</seg>
<seg id="60">The SAO did not have the comparative database needed to assess whether the funds were used economically in terms of the overall level of costs for bridges and tunnels on D 8.</seg>
<seg id="61">3.</seg>
<seg id="62">The SAO needed to ensure the effectiveness of the expenditure, taking into account the main technical parameters of the motorway, in particular the arrangement of bridges and tunnels, which should allow the same quality of the journey on both sides of the border.</seg>
<seg id="63">Following preparatory negotiations, the presidents of the two supreme audit institutions were signed on 4 January 2006 by the Coordinated Control Agreement on the D 8/A 17 motorway.</seg>
<seg id="64">The joint working meetings of the BRH and SAO inspectors took place throughout 2006 at an interval of approximately six to eight weeks.</seg>
<seg id="65">Current problems and tasks were addressed at the meetings, in particular the preparation of a uniform methodology for checking the prices of bridges and tunnels, the exchange of findings from the control of the border bridge construction and the preparation of joint reports.</seg>
<seg id="66">An important sign of cooperation was the ongoing exchange of information.</seg>
<seg id="67">While BRH carried out most of the work on comparing the technical parameters of bridges and tunnels and tender procedures, the SAO largely prepared a methodology for controlling the prices of bridges and tunnels.</seg>
<seg id="68">The applicable legal rules for government control differ in both countries in the way control actions are closed.</seg>
<seg id="69">For these reasons, the two highest audit institutions drew their own control conclusions on their findings, obtained during their inspections.</seg>
<seg id="70">This report reflects the results achieved in parallel checks.</seg>
<seg id="71">The cooperation will be completed by signing the final communiqué in the first half of 2007.</seg>
<seg id="72">Construction of the border bridge</seg>
<seg id="73">In the 2000 treaty, the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany agreed on a date for the completion of the construction of the border bridge, as far as possible, in 2005.</seg>
<seg id="74">The two sides then agreed to postpone this deadline until the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="75">The RMD was active as an investor.</seg>
<seg id="76">Germany is financially involved in the construction of the bridge from 42.13%.</seg>
<seg id="77">In the period up to 1999, the RMD proposed that the border bridge should have a prestressed reinforced concrete structure.</seg>
<seg id="78">In 1999, in agreement with its partners in Germany, the RMD agreed to a coupled steel-concrete structure.</seg>
<seg id="79">That decision was justified by a reduction in the number of double pillars from seven to five and the subsequent environmental benefits of such a solution to the valley.</seg>
<seg id="80">In addition, the comparative calculations carried out by the RMD stated that the coupled steel-concrete structure should be a less expensive option.</seg>
<seg id="81">But there was a mistake in the calculations.</seg>
<seg id="82">They stated that the new coupled steel-conconcrete structure would be only 397 m long.</seg>
<seg id="83">In fact, it's 5% longer.</seg>
<seg id="84">During the award of the contract for the border bridge, the RMD made serious errors.</seg>
<seg id="85">It has not prepared a custom dossier that adequately describes the assessment criteria and sub-criteria for comparing tenders.</seg>
<seg id="86">This error led to the evaluation and evaluation of tenders and the Director-General evaluating the bids in a subjective and problematic manner.</seg>
<seg id="87">The unsuccessful tenderer challenged the results of the contract procedure.</seg>
<seg id="88">A subsequent investigation by the Office for the Protection of Competition resulted in the contract for the award of the construction contract being signed later than originally envisaged.</seg>
<seg id="89">This meant that the 2004 summer construction season, after evaluating the bids, was wasted and the construction time was reduced.</seg>
<seg id="90">The construction company agreed to build the bridge in a shorter period of time, but at the cost of a substantial increase in costs.</seg>
<seg id="91">The offered procedure included a double assembly of the bridge superstructure, a change in the structure of the pillars and the establishment and equipment of the assembly space.</seg>
<seg id="92">In addition, the construction company was unable to procure the originally designed type of steel within the necessary time.</seg>
<seg id="93">The new type of steel – at a higher price by about €4 million, which had to be fully paid by the RMD – allowed for a reduction in the time to perform anti-corrosion protection, which in turn made it possible to reduce the overall construction time of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="94">Compared to the net price of €18.3 million offered in the tender, the total cost of building the border bridge will increase considerably as a result of the accelerated procedure and other adjustments in funding.</seg>
<seg id="95">The reduced time earmarked for construction work has led to a price increase of about €5.9 million.</seg>
<seg id="96">Currently, the net cost amount is around €25.9 million, without taking into account automatic price increases (as of October 2006).</seg>
<seg id="97">Comparison of prices of bridges and tunnels</seg>
<seg id="98">The two highest control institutions carried out an analysis of the prices of bridges on motorways D 8 and A 17 in order to identify bridges whose price was too high and to compare the prices of bridges on the German and Czech sides.</seg>
<seg id="99">The analysis was based on methods of mathematical statistics.</seg>
<seg id="100">Furthermore, tunnels on the D 8 were compared with similar tunnels on motorways in Germany (A 71, A 38 and A 4).</seg>
<seg id="101">There are no similar tunnels on the A 17 motorway.</seg>
<seg id="102">In preparing this part of the check, it was important to accurately identify the relevant prices.</seg>
<seg id="103">The two highest control institutions set the following principles for comparison of bridge prices: based on the actual price paid for the bridge without value added tax (VAT rates vary in the Czech Republic and SNR and are subject to change); disregard prices for special bridge foundations; rewrite prices in CZK at the rate of the European Central Bank valid as at 30 December 2005 (CZK 29 = € 1).</seg>
<seg id="104">On both D 8 and A 17, there are bridges of various structures (steelo-concrete, prestressed reinforced concrete, coupled steel-concrete and steel) and various sizes.</seg>
<seg id="105">In an effort to ensure the homogeneity of the structures studied, the bridges were divided into groups according to the type of structure.</seg>
<seg id="106">Within these groups, the size of the bridge was also taken into account in the analyses.</seg>
<seg id="107">By far the most common type of construction on both sides of the border were concrete bridges (20 bridges on D 8, 36 bridges on A 17).</seg>
<seg id="108">The analysis focused primarily on this group of bridges, as the number of the set allowed the use of mathematical-statistical methods with a high degree of reliability of the results.</seg>
<seg id="109">Checks found that prices per m 2 concrete bridges on both D 8 and A 17 depend on the size of the bridge (its length, area): the larger the bridge, the lower the price per m2 of the bridge structure.</seg>
<seg id="110">For German bridges, the price dependence on size was stronger than for Czech bridges (see charts below).</seg>
<seg id="111">Two concrete bridges on the A 17 and four on the D 8 have been identified, the price of which is significantly higher.</seg>
<seg id="112">A method was used to locate these bridges to detect atypical values in a set of numbers and a regression analysis taking into account the dependence of the price of the bridge on its size (for the determination of atypically expensive bridges, the standard distance from the regression curve upwards was used).</seg>
<seg id="113">However, information on the atypically high price of these bridges should only be seen as an indicator on which bridges need to be targeted.</seg>
<seg id="114">In order to draw a generally applicable conclusion, the reasons for the high price should be analysed in each identified case.</seg>
<seg id="115">One such cause may be inefficient administrative measures, or environmental protection requirements or any other acceptable reason.</seg>
<seg id="116">In view of the fact that Czech concrete bridges are on average longer than the German ones (see table below), the proven negative dependence of the price of the bridge on its length could lead to the assumption that Czech bridges should be cheaper.</seg>
<seg id="117">The lower prices of Czech concrete bridges are also supported by lower labour costs in the construction sector in the Czech Republic compared to Germany.</seg>
<seg id="118">On the contrary, the results of the analysis show that the prices of concrete bridges on the D 8 are higher than on the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="119">During the joint negotiations, two possible causes of this situation were identified:</seg>
<seg id="120">1.</seg>
<seg id="121">In Germany, most bridges are awarded as separate contracts.</seg>
<seg id="122">Such an award allows small and medium-sized regional firms to participate in the competition for the contract.</seg>
<seg id="123">In the Czech Republic, many bridges are awarded as part of a contract for part of the motorway route, which is several kilometres long.</seg>
<seg id="124">Small and medium-sized companies do not participate in such a competition because the contract is too big for them.</seg>
<seg id="125">2.</seg>
<seg id="126">There is greater variability in bridge structures in the Czech Republic than in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="127">In this context, the SAO found that the type of bridge structure was decided long before its construction.</seg>
<seg id="128">The decision shall be taken at the time when the RMD is submitting an application for a zoning decision.</seg>
<seg id="129">The RMD at this time selects types of bridges from multiple variants, but cost-effectiveness plays a minor role in decision-making.</seg>
<seg id="130">A general conclusion on the prices of bridges in the Czech Republic and Germany could only be reached on the basis of a thorough analysis of the construction work market in both countries, which would, however, go beyond this control action.</seg>
<seg id="131">The border bridge is the most expensive coupled steel-concrete bridge on D 8 and A 17.</seg>
<seg id="132">In the case of tunnels, it was found that the prices of the tunnels on the D 8 were twice as high as the tunnels in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="133">Comparing the main construction-technical parameters of the tunnels on the D 8 with the tunnels in Germany, however, showed no significant difference.</seg>
<seg id="134">Significant price differences could be attributed to the fact that there is no real competition in the field of tunnel construction in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="135">However, the small number of tunnels did not allow generally applicable conclusions to be drawn.</seg>
<seg id="136">Effectiveness and efficiency of the construction of the Dresden motorway – Prague</seg>
<seg id="137">The independent Czech Republic was established in 1993.</seg>
<seg id="138">In the same year, the government approved the concept of developing the motorway network.</seg>
<seg id="139">The D 8 motorway was to be gradually extended from Prague to the state border with Germany.</seg>
<seg id="140">Section 0805 through the Czech Central Mountains was to be taken before the border section no. 0807.</seg>
<seg id="141">The Czech Republic is acquiring the D 8 motorway as part of the programme financing.</seg>
<seg id="142">In programme No 327 220 "Construction of the D 8 motorway Prague – Ústí nad Labem – state border of the Czech Republic/SRN" set two targets for the construction of the D 8 motorway:</seg>
<seg id="143">1.</seg>
<seg id="144">improving the connection between Prague and Ústí nad Labem – national objective;</seg>
<seg id="145">2.</seg>
<seg id="146">improve the connection between Prague and Berlin within the IV Trans-European Transport Corridor Berlin-Istanbul - international target.</seg>
<seg id="147">According to the program, the construction of the section leading through the Czech Central Mountains was to be completed in June 2008 and the construction of the border section No 0807 in June 2007.</seg>
<seg id="148">It should be added here that the completion date is not identical to the date of commissioning.</seg>
<seg id="149">The SAO found that the preparation of the construction of the section leading through the Czech Central Mountains is now at the stage of an official zoning decision.</seg>
<seg id="150">Environmental activists challenged that decision with legal actions.</seg>
<seg id="151">The actions are not finally decided.</seg>
<seg id="152">It cannot therefore be excluded that the section running through the Czech Central Mountains will be completed a few years later than stated in the programme documentation.</seg>
<seg id="153">In the summer of 2006, the Czech Ministry of Transport proposed postponing the completion date of section No 0805 to 2010.</seg>
<seg id="154">As a result of these facts, the construction of the border section did not achieve a national goal – improving the connection between Prague and Ústí nad Labem.</seg>
<seg id="155">The RMD made an estimate of capital expenditure for the border section D 8 No 0807 and section No 0805 via the Czech Central Mountains in 1999-2001.</seg>
<seg id="156">The estimate for this capital expenditure of the included investment costs is about €639 million combined for both sections 0805 and 0807.</seg>
<seg id="157">Table 2: Economic assessment results (EIRR = internal rate of return)</seg>
<seg id="158">All the highways and expressways under consideration opened, both sections of the D 8 opened in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="159">On the northern part of the border section, the traffic intensity of 18,000 vehicles per day in 2010</seg>
<seg id="160">All the highways and expressways under consideration opened, both sections of the D 8 opened in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="161">On the northern part of the border section, the traffic intensity of 22,000 vehicles per day in 2010</seg>
<seg id="162">All the highways and expressways under consideration opened, both sections of the D 8 opened in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="163">On the northern part of the border section, the traffic intensity of 25,000 vehicles per day in 2010</seg>
<seg id="164">The economic analysis carried out in 2001 was based on the assumption that the border section and section through the Czech Central Mountains would be completed in time.</seg>
<seg id="165">At the time of the inspection, however, it is clear that the section through the Czech Central Mountains will not be opened at the original date.</seg>
<seg id="166">This will reduce the above EIRR values.</seg>
<seg id="167">The cost of both sections excluding VAT, calculated as at 31 December 2005, was € 897 million, or 27,4 % higher than the cost level with which the 2001 economic analysis worked.</seg>
<seg id="168">But there is a risk that section 0805 will be conducted in a different, more costly route, which would affect the aforementioned line of economic viability.</seg>
<seg id="169">Economic analysis showed that the construction of both sections of the motorway is economically viable at least 18,000 vehicles per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="170">The forecast for 2008 was 22,940 vehicles, but a study addressing the issue of itineraries for the missing section through the Czech Central Mountains envisages an intensity of 12,600 to 13,750 vehicles per day, pushing the investment below the economic viability threshold.</seg>
<seg id="171">With a higher load of itineraries for the missing section through the Czech Central Mountains, there is a high probability of congestion and thus an increase in external costs, which were not foreseen in the original economic analysis.</seg>
<seg id="172">The aforementioned reduction in revenues and cost increases means that the already low EIRR that the construction of the border section D 8 was not to be achieved.</seg>
<seg id="173">Construction of the D 8 border section is therefore inefficient.</seg>
<seg id="174">Also in the construction of the A 17 motorway, there was a similar cost overrucy as in the case of these two sections on D 8.</seg>
<seg id="175">As part of the overall economic assessment of the federal road development plan for long-distance transport for 1992, the Federal Ministry of Transport of Germany envisaged a cost of about €320 million.</seg>
<seg id="176">The resulting cost-to-income ratio was 4.6.</seg>
<seg id="177">In the meantime, however, costs have soared to about €670 million, and the cost-benefit ratio has more than halved.</seg>
<seg id="178">In addition to the parallel control carried out jointly with the SAO, the BRH audited the preparation and construction of the A 17 motorway in 2003 and 2005.</seg>
<seg id="179">In doing so, BRH found that the competent approval state authority had requested an off-road tunnel for Section A-17, which was not needed.</seg>
<seg id="180">During the inspection, BRH managed to convince the Federal Ministry and the German Road Construction Administration that the tunnel was not necessary.</seg>
<seg id="181">The result was savings, which amounted to roughly €10 million and €0.15 million in annual operating costs alone.</seg>
<seg id="182">When assessing the first Section A 17 BRH, BRH found that the construction project was not properly prepared.</seg>
<seg id="183">This is illustrated by the following example:</seg>
<seg id="184">At the preparatory stage, the Road Construction Administration did not investigate the conditions of the bedrock in the rocks of Dölzschen because the site was difficult to access.</seg>
<seg id="185">This was done only after the tunnel stamping machine hit a rock.</seg>
<seg id="186">Tests showed that the rocks inside were more weathered than anticipated during the selection process.</seg>
<seg id="187">Therefore, costly measures such as anchoring, injection and protective net against stone falling had to be taken, which required about €3.3 million.</seg>
<seg id="188">The Roads and Motorways Directorate had to bear the costs not only of other emergency operations, such as security measures in the rocks of Dölzschen, but also for measures that would not have been needed if the construction project had been properly prepared first.</seg>
<seg id="189">Expenditure of this kind includes the costs associated with the interruption of construction operations (€3.2 million), further training of drilling workers (€0.5 million) and rising wages and expenditure on goods as a result of exceeding the duration of the project (€7 million).</seg>
<seg id="190">The cost overruns thus amounted to around €10.7 million, which was not matched by any added value.</seg>
<seg id="191">Following the lessons learned from these and other audited projects, BRH asked the Federal Ministry to apply stricter management in its oversight of road construction work.</seg>
<seg id="192">The Federal Ministry should give the Road and Motorway Directorate the necessary incentive to implement quality assurance systems.</seg>
<seg id="193">Benefits of cooperation for BRH and SAO Cooperation fulfilled the intention of both audit institutions.</seg>
<seg id="194">BRH gained control knowledge of the preparation, assignment and course of the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="195">The two highest control institutions have built a database of the prices of bridges and tunnels, on which future controls will be able to rely.</seg>
<seg id="196">The SAO found that the main construction-technical parameters of bridges, tunnels and the route of the D 8 motorway are no different from the A 17 parameters.</seg>
<seg id="197">The inspectors of the two institutions involved in the cooperation have gained new experience, which they can use for further inspections.</seg>
</p>
