<p>
<seg id="1">Procurement of public works contracts and the prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint Parallel Control Report by the Czech Supreme Audit Office (SAO) and the German Federal Court of Auditors (BRH)</seg>
<seg id="3">Introduction and overview</seg>
<seg id="4">Public procurement of goods and services by contracting authorities is very important for both the state and private spheres.</seg>
<seg id="5">The role of the state is to use public resources as efficiently and economically as possible and to ensure fair and regulated free competition.</seg>
<seg id="6">In the European Union (EU), public procurement is a key factor in the success of the Single Economic Area.</seg>
<seg id="7">In its rules, the EU has set limits whereby the contracting authority must comply with certain requirements to guarantee a broad and unlimited competitive environment across the EU.</seg>
<seg id="8">EU Member States must therefore transpose European procurement law into their national legislation and put it into practice.</seg>
<seg id="9">Both the Czech Republic and Germany have already done so.</seg>
<seg id="10">For public procurement that are values below EU limits, regulation of their procurement remains within the remit of individual countries.</seg>
<seg id="11">Moreover, public procurement is prone to corruption with the consequent high potential for damage.</seg>
<seg id="12">Therefore, contracting entities are obliged to take reasonable measures in their procurement procedures to prevent corruption and incorrect favouritism (prevention of corruption).</seg>
<seg id="13">In January 2011, the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (Czech SAI - SAO) and the Federal Court of Auditors of Germany (German SAI - BRH) agreed to carry out parallel checks on procurement procedures and the prevention of corruption in land and transport constructions.</seg>
<seg id="14">Cooperation was also focused on the area of European procurement law as transposed into national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="15">The checks included procurement below European limits in order to penalise the area of corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="16">The audit findings of the two supreme audit institutions are summarised in a joint report, which is addressed, inter alia, to international organisations such as the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).</seg>
<seg id="17">Control areas and audited institutions</seg>
<seg id="18">The BRH assessment is based on blanket checks of the aforementioned areas carried out on German building administrations responsible for federal transport and land constructions between 2011 and 2012.</seg>
<seg id="19">For example, highway construction and large-scale building projects were evaluated.</seg>
<seg id="20">BRH included findings from past inspections in the evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="21">The SAO evaluation is based on inspections carried out during the years 2008 to 2012, which focused on construction of roads, railway lines, water projects, large buildings (hospitals, cultural facilities, universities) and some other buildings in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="22">In Germany, the award of federal public contracts is mostly carried out by the provincial construction administrations.</seg>
<seg id="23">In the Czech Republic, public procurement in the area of transport infrastructure is the responsibility of state institutions for road and railway construction.</seg>
<seg id="24">In the field of building construction, public procurement is carried out by beneficiaries of budget funds.</seg>
<seg id="25">In both countries, the services of external experts are also used at the various stages of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="26">The evaluation must take into account differences in public procurement legislation and the specificities of the construction market in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="27">Structure of the Public Procurement Act in both countries</seg>
<seg id="28">In Germany, the conduct of European procurement procedures is governed by laws and subordinate standards.</seg>
<seg id="29">Procurement procedures limited to Germany are governed by budgetary law and the relevant administrative acts .</seg>
<seg id="30">Internal administrative rules contain numerous additional provisions for both European and national procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="31">Further details on the requirements of European procurement law and the prevention of corruption are enshrined in the so-called federal government tender manuals, in which the requirements are elaborated or formulated in greater detail with regard to legal precedents in the area of procurement law.</seg>
<seg id="32">In the Czech Republic, public procurement is governed by the Public Procurement Act and other legislation relating to contracts with value above and below European limits.</seg>
<seg id="33">The terms of reference were made to substantial changes in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="34">The new rules have strengthened the transparency of procurement procedures, opened up room for more competition and reduced opportunities for corruption during the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="35">Basic aspects of procurement law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="36">As regards European procurement procedures, open and narrower procedures in particular need to be applied in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="37">In Germany, contracts below the European limit are awarded in accordance with national regulations (public call for competition, limited call for participation, negotiated procedure), but these are virtually identical to the above conditions for the European procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="38">Public procurement in Germany is characterised by the principle of preference for open procedures (where candidates on a European scale are invited) and public calls for participation (only in the case of national procedures).</seg>
<seg id="39">In open procedures and when calling for competition, any bidder may submit an offer.</seg>
<seg id="40">Another important feature of German procurement law is the support of small and medium-sized firms.</seg>
<seg id="41">This is achieved primarily by splitting the overall public contract into commercially specific parts and dividing into sub-contracts.</seg>
<seg id="42">The award of contracts divided into these parts gives the opportunity to participate in the proceedings as many candidates as possible.</seg>
<seg id="43">The two characteristics of German procurement law are time-tested instruments for obtaining good value for money.</seg>
<seg id="44">In Germany, more than 330,000 construction companies are registered with 1.9 million employees.</seg>
<seg id="45">In the Czech Republic, the conditions of European procedures must be applied even in cases of public procurement with a value below the EU limit.</seg>
<seg id="46">The exception is a simplified sub-prime procedure where the contracting authority can use less demanding procedures.</seg>
<seg id="47">In accordance with European law, Czech procurement law includes the conditions under which the contract must be awarded in order to ensure competition and achieve a favourable price.</seg>
<seg id="48">The current Czech legislation allows contracting authorities to choose between open management and closer management.</seg>
<seg id="49">85,000 construction companies are registered in the Czech Republic, of which about 1,900 have 20 or more employees.</seg>
<seg id="50">Total number of contracting authorities for public works and share of individual types of procedure in both countries</seg>
<seg id="51">In 2011, the total volume of construction work in Germany amounted to 7 675 billion.</seg>
<seg id="52">Of which CZK 1,138 billion (15%) was the share of public contracts, which, in addition to contracts awarded by the federal government, included contracts awarded by individual Länder and municipalities.</seg>
<seg id="53">The total volume of projects of the federal road and earthworks (without the construction of railways and water constructions) amounted to CZK 212.5 billion.</seg>
<seg id="54">In 2011, the composition of federal contracts for land works and transport works was as follows: 80.7% open procedures and public calls; 12.7% closer management and narrower calls;</seg>
<seg id="55">6.6% of the negotiated procedure and direct procurement; 33.2% is the share of European procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="56">The volume of public construction contracts in the Czech Republic in 2011 reached CZK 118.6 billion , which was about 25% of the total volume of all construction works.</seg>
<seg id="57">In 2009, it reached CZK 194.0 billion, which was 37% of the total.</seg>
<seg id="58">Structure of procurement types in 2011: 65.1% open procedure; 14.3% narrower procedure; 9.5% negotiated procedure; 8.4% simplified procedures for sub-prime contracts; 2.7% other procedures.</seg>
<seg id="59">The figures include all public supply, service and works contracts awarded by contracting authorities in 2011.</seg>
<seg id="60">These figures show that: parallel controls in both countries have been targeted at a substantial part of public procurement procedures; the prevention of corruption, which must still be taken into account in procurement procedures, has a significant financial impact; open relevance. procurement procedures are of key importance.</seg>
<seg id="61">Summary of the main results</seg>
<seg id="62">The SAO and BRH carried out parallel controls on the award of European works contracts, with an emphasis on the prevention of corruption in their countries.</seg>
<seg id="63">The checks focused on comparing the legislation in both countries and the EU and on the implementation of public procurement in the field of land and transport construction.</seg>
<seg id="64">The key findings are also provided:</seg>
<seg id="65">The EU Public Procurement Directive has been transposed into the national rights of both countries (points 1 and 3.1).</seg>
<seg id="66">Preventing corruption is not only the aim of the EU directive, but of the national procurement rules of the two countries, which differ in part in terms of focus and in detail.</seg>
<seg id="67">In both countries, the essential requirement to comply with the tender documents is the inclusion of all the information needed to prepare tenders.</seg>
<seg id="68">The specification shall be neutral and shall not contain any requirements restricting competition.</seg>
<seg id="69">The tender documents in Germany generally meet these requirements.</seg>
<seg id="70">In the Czech Republic, the problem is the lack of definition of the subject of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="71">In Germany, a division of contracts is required into parts where it is only possible in order to promote a competitive environment.</seg>
<seg id="72">According to BRH's findings, this requirement is respected in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="73">The SAO's inspections showed that significant heavy public works in the field of road construction are commissioned in the Czech Republic without being divided into parts or divided into parts, but only into a very significant volume. This method can distort competition and lead to restrictions on only a few large companies.</seg>
<seg id="74">These limitations on market potential can result in significant cost increases and give rise to the risk of non-serious price negotiations and inadmissible conventions.</seg>
<seg id="75">The legislation in both countries allows contracting authorities, under certain conditions, to retrospectively outsource further works if this need arises after the conclusion of the contract (point 4.1).</seg>
<seg id="76">In both countries, the requirements for the correct determination of the type of procurement procedure are met.</seg>
<seg id="77">In the Czech Republic, under the applicable regulations, contracting entities can freely designate one of the open procurement procedures, namely an open procedure or a narrower procedure.</seg>
<seg id="78">German regulations in tendering and budgetary law enshrine the primacy of open procedures for both European tenders and national ones, known as public calls for competition.</seg>
<seg id="79">Open procurement procedures in both countries allow a larger range of bidders to submit a bid and also reduce the risk of corruption because they make it difficult to negotiate prices illegally between bidders.</seg>
<seg id="80">At the same time, the best results in value for money are achieved.</seg>
<seg id="81">In the case of large contracts whose projected total price is or exceeds the limits set by the EU, the audited contracting entities have always tendered a European procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="82">In determining the type of procurement procedure, the correct determination of the estimated value of the contract plays a very important role.</seg>
<seg id="83">In Germany, databases are used to objectively determine the price of public works, in which the values are based on completed construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="84">This is an objective enough tool.</seg>
<seg id="85">In the Czech Republic, databases are used only in the area of road construction, but they are not yet an effective tool (point 4.2).</seg>
<seg id="86">When awarding a works contract according to European procurement procedures, it is necessary to publish preliminary information and notice of the initiation of a procurement procedure, in order to strengthen competition by allowing interested parties to prepare in a timely manner for the submission of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="87">As a rule, the construction authorities audited complied with this requirement.</seg>
<seg id="88">In isolated cases, errors in the information released, incorrect application of provisions and/or a lack of controls may have impaired competition (item 4.3).</seg>
<seg id="89">When selecting candidates to participate in a narrower procurement procedure, there is a greater risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="90">Under EU law, the number of candidates invited must be high enough to guarantee real competition.</seg>
<seg id="91">The selection criteria must be objective, non-discriminatory and published well in advance.</seg>
<seg id="92">Beyond EU requirements, contracting authorities in both countries should, as often as possible, rotate candidates who call for participation in the procedure when selecting suppliers.</seg>
<seg id="93">In Germany, there are partly very detailed requirements to prevent the risks of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="94">In some cases, the audited contracting entities did not comply with these requirements.</seg>
<seg id="95">In the Czech Republic, selection decisions were not always credible (point 4.4).</seg>
<seg id="96">In both countries, contracting entities must ensure during the procurement procedure that all candidates wishing to submit a tender receive the same information.</seg>
<seg id="97">Any agreements between those candidates and between them and third parties involved in the preparation of the specifications must, as far as possible, be prevented in order to avoid restricting competition in the form of unlawful agreements.</seg>
<seg id="98">In Germany, the measures are more thorough than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="99">However, the audited German contracting entities did not meet the requirement in several cases (paragraph 4.5).</seg>
<seg id="100">In both countries, the principle of cross-checking and transparency must be applied when opening envelopes.</seg>
<seg id="101">The labelling, documentation, protection and confidentiality requirements are intended to limit the scope for manipulation and are particularly detailed in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="102">Checks in both countries found only a few cases of irregularities (point 4.6).</seg>
<seg id="103">The assessment and evaluation of bids is procedurally regulated in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="104">The relevant German measures are more complex, but it has not always been respected by the audited contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="105">For example, contracting entities forwarded their bids to third parties for consultation without their prior assessment, without properly documenting any suspicious circumstances.</seg>
<seg id="106">The offers were thus insufficiently protected against subsequent manipulations (point 4.7).</seg>
<seg id="107">Participants must be concerned about the intended award of the contract for legal protection enterprises are to be informed about the intended contract award before the latter is finalised.</seg>
<seg id="108">This legal protection rule also is designed to prevent corruptive action.</seg>
<seg id="109">The law of the Czech Republic provides for judicial review of contract award procedures also for national tenders.</seg>
<seg id="110">Only in few cases, the notification of the enterprises was not appropriately ensured (item 4.8).</seg>
<seg id="111">The procurement procedure documentation was not always complete or entirely credible for the audited contracting entities in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="112">In the case of several procurement procedures, the transparency requirements applied at European level have not always been properly complied with in the minutes of the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="113">In addition, some identified deficiencies reduced the preventive anti-corruption function of the dossier.</seg>
<seg id="114">Contracting entities in both countries mostly fulfilled their reporting obligations (point 4.9).</seg>
<seg id="115">Summary of the guiding principles of European procurement law and corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="116">European Award law</seg>
<seg id="117">In order to ensure free competition in the EU, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union have adopted, inter alia, a Directive on the coordination of procedures for the award of public works contracts, public supply contracts and public service contracts in order to ensure the free movement of goods and services and the Directive on the coordination of laws, regulations and administrative provisions relating to the award of public supply contracts and public works contracts (Right Procedures Directive), the two Directives being transposed into national law.</seg>
<seg id="118">The EU's general procurement principles include in particular: a requirement for a competitive environment; a requirement for equal treatment or non-discrimination; a requirement for transparency.</seg>
<seg id="119">EU procurement principles include the Directive on the Coordination of Public Procurement Procedures, in addition, includes provisions relating to construction projects with a total estimated value of more than €5 million.</seg>
<seg id="120">These provisions affect: the content of the procurement documents; the type of procurement procedure used; the publication of certain information before, during and after the end of the procedure; compliance with the deadline for receipt of tenders; the qualification requirements that may be required of tenderers; the criteria for selecting the most appropriate tender.</seg>
<seg id="121">The legal protection of candidates is governed by the Review Procedures Directive.</seg>
<seg id="122">In the event of a potential breach of contract law, tenderers may have the contracting authority's decision reviewed in accordance with the review procedures.</seg>
<seg id="123">Both countries transposed EU requirements into national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="124">Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="125">Importance of corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="126">In none of the two countries, there is no legal definition of what corruption actually means.</seg>
<seg id="127">In general, corruption is seen as an abuse of a personal (confidential) position for one's own benefit.</seg>
<seg id="128">As a rule, this means that such misuse is encouraged by those who benefit.</seg>
<seg id="129">Corruption can be a barrier to competition and can cause serious economic losses.</seg>
<seg id="130">It is estimated that the total damage related to corruption amounts to 5% of the world's economic output.</seg>
<seg id="131">For the EU area, these costs are estimated at 1% of the EU's economic performance.</seg>
<seg id="132">Where a contracting authority is involved, conventions restricting competition or allowing dishonest conduct may weaken confidence in the integrity, ability and overall work of the public administration.</seg>
<seg id="133">Therefore, the prevention of corruption is an essential task for contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="134">Both practice and procedures must be controlled, in particular, in areas particularly susceptible to corruption, in order to take adequate measures to prevent it.</seg>
<seg id="135">Adopting preventive measures and carrying out effective controls can substantially reduce the susceptibility of the decision-making process to corruption.</seg>
<seg id="136">As a rule, the award of works contracts is considered to be particularly susceptible to corruption.</seg>
<seg id="137">Measures on the prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="138">In Germany, corruption is prosecutable under criminal and labour law, which mainly concerns active and passive bribery, acceptance and offering significant benefits.</seg>
