<seg id="644">Where there is a suspicion in Germany of conduct intended to limit competition, the contracting authority is obliged to report this fact without delay to the competent superior authority.</seg>
<seg id="645">This must decide on the way forward and whether it is appropriate to inform the antitrust authority or law enforcement authorities.</seg>
<seg id="646">It must also approve (e.g. if the contract exceeds €50,000 and the contract has not been awarded to the tenderer with the lowest bid), whether the contract will be awarded when the contract is negotiated or whether the procurement procedure will be cancelled.</seg>
<seg id="647">Czech rules do not regulate this area.</seg>
<seg id="648">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="649">BRH</seg>
<seg id="650">Examination of suitability and procurement criteria</seg>
<seg id="651">Most of the procurement procedures examined were in line with the relevant requirements.</seg>
<seg id="652">In the case of some recommendations by potential suppliers made by self-employed workers, the contracting authorities themselves did not check the suitability of the tenderers themselves.</seg>
<seg id="653">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="654">In some cases of procurement procedures, insufficient documentation was submitted as to whether the contracting authority took into account all published evaluation criteria or whether the selection decision was based solely on the price criterion.</seg>
<seg id="655">Selection of interested persons and confidentiality of offers</seg>
<seg id="656">Some contracting authorities used the services of unauthorized persons, such as self-employed workers or employees of construction offices.</seg>
<seg id="657">They were incorporated into the planning or implementation process of construction projects, performing functions that were to be held exclusively by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="658">Contracting entities have sought to substantiate this with their lack of human resources in the sector.</seg>
<seg id="659">In some cases, self-employed professionals used to review the offers of services of persons who were not formally bound to maintain the confidentiality of tenders and to perform with due care the fulfilment of their obligations under the contract.</seg>
<seg id="660">As far as contracting authorities are concerned, there was generally no evidence of whether offers in the custody of self-employed professionals were available only to designated persons.</seg>
<seg id="661">Review and mathematical control of bids</seg>
<seg id="662">Some contracting authorities have handed over open envelopes for further examination to self-employed professionals without first carrying out the prescribed verification of tenders and mathematical examination and without documenting the results of these examinations.</seg>
<seg id="663">In the event of any intent to manipulate, third parties could make changes to the bids that could not be identified by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="664">The examination of documents revealed a number of cases where unusual elements in the bids were not adequately labelled or where data on prices and products were missing.</seg>
<seg id="665">Performance audits</seg>
<seg id="666">A model check by one contracting authority revealed that in 75% of procurement cases, the most advantageous tenders deviated by more than 10% from pre-arranged costs.</seg>
<seg id="667">One of the 20 procurement procedures was cancelled due to inadequate bidding prices.</seg>
<seg id="668">In many cases, there was a lack of evidence or sufficient documentation on the examination of bids or negotiations with tenderers for further clarification.</seg>
<seg id="669">In many cases, detailed information was also lacking, for example, about unit prices of the most important invoiced items.</seg>
<seg id="670">The reason for the derogations were often cited changes in market prices or increases in material costs.</seg>
<seg id="671">Contracting authorities have argued that identifying and proving compensatory prices is difficult.</seg>
<seg id="672">In the case of one call for tenders made by an entity outside the ordinary contracting entity, a 66 % lower price was offered compared to the initial cost estimate.</seg>
<seg id="673">No data on a closer examination of the cost or on the determination of the reasons for the deviations were not recorded.</seg>
<seg id="674">In clarifying this issue, the contracting authority found no indication of price dumping for the tenderer to whom the contract was eventually awarded.</seg>
<seg id="675">It was therefore not clarified whether the initial cost estimate was excessive or whether the price offered was too low.</seg>
<seg id="676">Later, the contracting authority of that tenderer was assessed as a "low-cost company" which was unable to meet either qualitative requirements or deadlines.</seg>
<seg id="677">In another procurement procedure, the contracting authority awarded the contract to a tenderer whose price was 35 % higher than the initial cost estimate.</seg>
<seg id="678">The contracting authority did not cancel the tendering procedure and put forward an unfounded argument that the tenderer could be presumed not to have incurred a disproportionately high cost setting of its prices.</seg>
<seg id="679">Suspicion of irregularities</seg>
<seg id="680">Two incidents of irregularities were found with one contracting authority, and they were reported to a company responsible for technical supervision.</seg>
<seg id="681">In one procurement procedure, two bidders submitted bids containing an identical price calculation, prompting the contracting authorities to exclude both bids.</seg>
<seg id="682">The inspections did not show any material shortcomings in the application of other provisions.</seg>
<seg id="683">SAO</seg>
<seg id="684">Verification of suitability</seg>
<seg id="685">For many construction actions, such as university buildings, roads and railways, contracting entities have not excluded tenderers from participating in the procurement procedure, even though they did not meet the requirements of the contracting authority referred to in the terms of reference, or did not substantiate the qualifications to the extent required, or, on the contrary, one contracting authority could not substantiate or explain the reason for the exclusion of the candidate who met the requirements.</seg>
<seg id="686">Evaluation</seg>
<seg id="687">For the construction of the wastewater treatment plant, the individual evaluation criteria of the tender procedure for the contractor of the construction were determined, but the contracting authority did not respect them during the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="688">For actions in the field of railway infrastructure development, the weighting of the evaluation criteria for the award of the contract was not determined at the initiation of the procedure, but only at the beginning of the evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="689">For the road repair project, the assessment of the criterion of "shortening construction time" was not carried out correctly.</seg>
<seg id="690">For bidders in second and third place, the evaluation incorrectly stated a greater reduction in the construction time than indicated in their tenders.</seg>
<seg id="691">Documentation of the reasons for the selection of the candidate</seg>
<seg id="692">For the three housing promotion actions, the contracting authority did not substantiate on the basis of which criteria it assessed the offers received and how it selected the most suitable of them.</seg>
<seg id="693">Correctness of the selection of suppliers of small-scale contracts associated with the construction of a ring road with an estimated price of up to 500 thousand.</seg>
<seg id="694">The CZK could not be verified because the suppliers were selected only on the basis of telephone consultations on the price and date of fulfilment, but the documents on these negotiations were not prepared.</seg>
<seg id="695">Summary</seg>
<seg id="696">In both countries, the rules for the verification and evaluation of bids correspond to EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="697">However, it differs in the light of the specific management steps and the selection of individuals involved in the management.</seg>
<seg id="698">Unlike in the Czech Republic, these steps in the procurement process are governed by stricter and more detailed requirements, especially as regards the application of the cross-price principle and the protection of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="699">The same applies to the rules for verifying the appropriateness of the prices offered.</seg>
<seg id="700">In both countries, in some cases of checks, it was found that substantial steps of the process in the verification and evaluation of the bids were not documented at all and, if so, only partially.</seg>
<seg id="701">The absence of control tools and transparency in decision-making during the review and evaluation of tenders allows for manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="702">The checks showed serious defects, such as the transmission of bids to third parties without prior appropriate examination and documenting the tenders by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="703">Where contracting entities entrust a third party with the performance of the functions associated with the examination and evaluation of tenders, appropriate measures and increased control of measures against increased handling options are necessary.</seg>
<seg id="704">When checking price legitimacy, the audited German contracting authorities did not use the complete set of available instruments in all cases and did not deal with their own pricing structure.</seg>
<seg id="705">In the Czech Republic, deficiencies were identified in the evaluation of the suitability of tenders and the application of evaluation criteria.</seg>
<seg id="706">Completion of procurement procedure</seg>
<seg id="707">After examining and evaluating the tenders, the procurement process is completed by awarding the contract or cancelling the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="708">Requirements of European law and the prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="709">In the case of a European procedure, all tenderers must be informed in advance of the award decision.</seg>
<seg id="710">Suppliers shall have the opportunity to review the decision taken within a limited period of 10 or 15 days and to request its examination where appropriate.</seg>
<seg id="711">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="712">The period of 10 days shall apply to electronic submissions and 15 days to other submissions.</seg>
<seg id="713">The contract shall not be concluded before the expiry of that period or before the review procedure has expired.</seg>
<seg id="714">If the review body rejects the complaint and confirms the decision, candidates and tenderers must be given the opportunity to have the right to be reviewed by an independent court.</seg>
<seg id="715">This measure ensures that no contracting authority will be able to circumvent the legal protection of suppliers by rapidly implementing the decision of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="716">The contracting authority must properly document the conduct of the proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="717">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="718">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="719">Both countries implemented management information obligations.</seg>
<seg id="720">In both countries, the final decision on the outcome of the procurement procedure lies with the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="721">However, he cannot arbitrarily deviate from the results of a properly carried out examination and evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="722">The contracting authority is to conclude the contract within a specified period of time.</seg>
<seg id="723">This is due to the fact that the tenderer is not bound by its tender after that period has expired.</seg>
<seg id="724">The content of the contract must not deviate from the winning bid.</seg>
<seg id="725">Failed bidders are to be informed of the outcome in a timely manner, stating the reason why their bid was not accepted.</seg>
<seg id="726">The cancellation of the procurement procedure is only permissible if certain conditions are met, e.g. if the prices in tenders do not correspond to the specifications.</seg>
<seg id="727">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="728">In the Czech Republic, the mandatory waiting period prior to the conclusion of the contract covers both European and national procedures.</seg>
<seg id="729">In Germany, the equivalent provision applies only to European procedures.</seg>
<seg id="730">In all other procedures in Germany, tenderers cannot be informed of the award of the contract before deciding on its EU provisions and review award.</seg>
<seg id="731">In the Czech Republic, the tendering procedure must be cancelled if a single tender has been received or only a single tender met the requirements for its consideration and evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="732">In Germany, the contract must be awarded even if a single tender has been received, provided that the tender fulfils the conditions set out in the tender documents and is cost-effective.</seg>
<seg id="733">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="734">BRH</seg>
<seg id="735">The checks found few discrepancies in the completion of the audited procurement processes.</seg>
<seg id="736">In some cases, European procedures have received authorising letters before the expiry of the notification period, which may invalidate the contract.</seg>
<seg id="737">Also, in several cases of open procedures, the authorising letters of modification were incompatible with the content of the tender, such as new deadlines.</seg>
<seg id="738">In some cases, the contracting authorities did not meet the time limits for awarding the contract.</seg>
<seg id="739">In one open procedure, the contracting authority selected the second most advantageous tender because the bidder offering a price more than 50% lower no longer wished to fulfil the contract at the price originally offered.</seg>
<seg id="740">SAO</seg>
<seg id="741">During the reconstruction and construction of the university, in one case the contracting authority did not conclude a contract with the contractor in accordance with the draft contract contained in the tenderer's tender.</seg>
<seg id="742">For some road repair and maintenance actions, highway construction and ring roads, contracts were concluded later than stipulated by law.</seg>
<seg id="743">For building modifications in former military installations, the contracting authority sent a notice of the selection of the most suitable tender to all bidders only after the legal deadline had expired.</seg>
<seg id="744">Summary</seg>
<seg id="745">Both countries implemented EU rules on the termination of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="746">The legal protection of unsuccessful candidates contributes to reducing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="747">The Czech Public Procurement Act includes an institute of legal protection even in cases of contracts below EU limits.</seg>
<seg id="748">In both countries, it was found that the limited time limit for concluding the contract was exceeded.</seg>
<seg id="749">This can cause adverse economic consequences and increase the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="750">In the future, contracting entities should eliminate such shortcomings in the conclusion of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="751">Documentation, notifications, information obligations</seg>
<seg id="752">The procurement process, with all its various stages, relevant findings and decisions, including the relevant justifications, shall be documented in a transparent manner.</seg>
<seg id="753">Completion of the procurement procedure at European level must be published.</seg>
<seg id="754">Data on procurement procedures are summarised in EU statistics.</seg>
<seg id="755">Requirements of European law and the prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="756">The obligation to document procurement procedures is in line with the essential requirement of the principle of transparency, applied at EU-wide level.</seg>
<seg id="757">Only a proper and time-consuming decision-making and justification documentation gives a guarantee of transparency in the procurement process and, above all, guarantees effective legal protection of the interests of each tenderer in cases where the value of the contract exceeds the European limits.</seg>
<seg id="758">The relevant documentation is also an essential part of the anti-corruption measures, as the obligation to substantiate individual decisions in detail and their merits significantly reduce the scope for manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="759">In cases of European procurement procedures, the contracting authority must notify the completion of the EU Publications Office (EU's Office of Official Publications) within 48 days from the date of award of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="760">The Authority publishes a notification in the EU's Official Journal and this also fulfils the transparency requirement.</seg>
<seg id="761">The contracting authority must summarise the essential information on its procurement procedures and communicate them to the European Commission through the relevant national ministries.</seg>
<seg id="762">On this basis, the European Commission issues annual statistics that make it possible to get an overview of the development of the single market in the field of construction.</seg>
<seg id="763">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="764">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="765">Both countries have fully transposed into their national legislation the provisions of the European law on documentation and notification obligations.</seg>
<seg id="766">The provisions on documentation and notification for the purposes of European statistics are almost identical in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="767">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="768">In the Czech Republic, the obligation to announce the award of a contract applies not only to European procedures, but also to national procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="769">The notification period is only 15 days from the conclusion of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="770">In Germany, the obligation to notify procurement procedures, in addition to those that are mandatory under European law, applies only to limited procedures exceeding the limit of €25 thousand ($625,000) and direct procedures exceeding the limit of €15,000 ($375,000) including VAT.</seg>
<seg id="771">Only the parties to the proceedings are informed below this limit.</seg>
<seg id="772">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="773">BRH</seg>
<seg id="774">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="775">A large number of assignments have not been fully documented.</seg>
<seg id="776">The notification did not contain all the necessary information, e.g. the reasons for the delivery specifications and the national rules.</seg>
<seg id="777">In the case of one procedure, the contracting authority did not explain why it had concluded a contract with a tenderer whose tender did not contain mandatory requirements.</seg>
<seg id="778">In several cases, some required records were also missing.</seg>
<seg id="779">Publication of award</seg>
<seg id="780">In the case of some European procedures, the contracting authority erred in the publication of the notice.</seg>
<seg id="781">In the case of several terms of reference, there was no evidence of disclosure of the notice.</seg>
<seg id="782">Reporting obligation</seg>
<seg id="783">The statistically proven files included the required minimum of information and were created and sent in time.</seg>
<seg id="784">Preliminary transparency</seg>
<seg id="785">In most cases, the contracting authority published information about the outcome of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="786">In the case of one contracting authority, contract information was not disclosed due to a communication error.</seg>
<seg id="787">It took the contracting authority six months to notice the error.</seg>
<seg id="788">Consequently, the outcome of the proceedings was not disclosed during that period.</seg>
<seg id="789">SAO</seg>
<seg id="790">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="791">For events related to the organisation of a major sporting event, significant deficiencies were identified in the documentation of the course of the procurement procedure, such as incorrect information on bidding prices in the evaluation committee's discussions.</seg>
<seg id="792">In addition, some documents on opening envelopes have not been signed.</seg>
<seg id="793">Publication of award</seg>
<seg id="794">In the preparation of repairs and maintenance of roads, the construction of the motorway and the ring road, the announcement of the award of the public contract was sent after the deadline or it was not made public.</seg>
<seg id="795">Summary</seg>
<seg id="796">The provisions on documentation and notification and notification obligations include European requirements and are almost identical in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="797">This generally ensures the transparency of procurement procedures and final selection.</seg>
<seg id="798">Czech reporting obligations are somewhat stricter compared to German ones.</seg>
<seg id="799">The inspections have identified shortcomings substantially reducing the value of documentation as a means of preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="800">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="801">Contracting entities should continue to strengthen the transparency of their procurement procedures and fully meet the notification and notification requirements.</seg>
<seg id="802">Aggregate evaluation and recommendations</seg>
<seg id="803">Parallel controls of the SAO and BRH were focused on two areas that are essential for the public procurement process both in the Czech Republic and Germany, namely the application of EU procurement law and the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="804">EU legislation gives opportunities to international competition within the EU to create a single European market.</seg>
<seg id="805">Measures aimed at preventing corruption are not only to avoid or at least reduce it, but also to prevent financial damage and potential loss of confidence in the integrity of the government.</seg>
<seg id="806">The audited supervisory findings of the two audit institutions - the SAO and BRH - with regard to the application of the procurement law of both countries and the comparison of its relevant provisions, give an internal view of the common and distinct elements which may assist both countries in the further development and application of this right.</seg>
<seg id="807">Application of EU procurement law</seg>
<seg id="808">Both countries have transposed EU public procurement law into their national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="809">In both countries, there is thus an important common base for public procurement and the fulfilment of essential requirements in the field of: competition; equal treatment of candidates; transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="810">Contracting entities reinforce these requirements in part with very large measures.</seg>
<seg id="811">The Czech Republic has extended the provisions on public procurement requiring European procedures to procedures below EU limits and are therefore governed by national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="812">However, the checks have shown that contracting entities are not always fully in line with all relevant provisions of EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="813">German contracting entities should continue to improve the quality of their procurement procedures in order to eliminate the aforementioned irregularities taking into account the implementation of EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="814">In the Czech Republic, the controls identified risks affecting economy and achieving value for money.</seg>
<seg id="815">These include, in particular, the incomplete definition of the subject-matter of the public contract, which resulted in additional works which were often awarded in breach of the law, the lack of definition of the anticipated price and the required qualification prerequisites narrowing the possible circle of tenderers and thus reducing competition especially in the field of transport constructions.</seg>
<seg id="816">Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="817">Joint controls were not intended to detect corruption cases.</seg>
<seg id="818">The reason was that both BRH and the SAO did not have sufficient tools to do so.</seg>
<seg id="819">However, they can examine whether the competent authorities of both countries are taking measures to reduce corruption and manipulation in public procurement and how these measures are applied.</seg>
<seg id="820">When it comes to preventing corruption, both countries have focused on different aspects.</seg>
<seg id="821">Above all, German provisions give room for broad and unlimited competition, transparency and controls as a central element in the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="822">Czech regulations mainly monitor the strengthening of the transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="823">BRH</seg>
<seg id="824">In Germany, there are general principles for the prevention of corruption that apply to the entire federal administration.</seg>
<seg id="825">These principles were also included among the procurement requirements and were adopted to meet the specific needs of such procurement.</seg>
<seg id="826">The relevant provisions specify, at times with great precision, ways of complying with the requirements for preventing corruption during the procurement procedure and the selection of persons incorporated therein.</seg>
<seg id="827">In BRH's view, the principle of preference for open procurement and calls for participation is a particularly appropriate tool for substantially reducing the risk of corruption in public procurement, while restricting competition increases the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="828">Risk analysis and adequate controls (particularly the principle of cross-checking), transparency requirements, procurement documents and various organisational measures are also an effective mechanism to prevent corruption and manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="829">BRH therefore does not feel the need for substantial changes to the current provisions that public institutions have to comply with in public procurement.</seg>
<seg id="830">Anti-corruption measures are widely applied in practice.</seg>
<seg id="831">Irregularities found in some areas have highlighted weaknesses in compliance with certain requirements.</seg>
<seg id="832">Therefore, contracting authorities should provide further training to their staff, familiarising them with anti-corruption requirements and further raising their awareness in this area.</seg>
<seg id="833">A significant proportion of the weaknesses revealed apply to activities delegated by the building administration to private entrepreneurs.</seg>
<seg id="834">However, the absence of adequate controls in delegating powers increases the risk of abuse.</seg>
<seg id="835">Activities susceptible to manipulation and corruption should therefore only be passed on to third parties if the administration can guarantee a sufficient degree of protection against unauthorised interference.</seg>
<seg id="836">SAO</seg>
<seg id="837">Anti-corruption strategies have been adopted at the government level in the Czech Republic, which also significantly affect the area of public procurement.</seg>
<seg id="838">The SAO's auditing actions took place during the period when one of the most important parts of this strategy was implemented, namely a significant change to the Public Procurement Act and the adoption of follow-up implementing regulations.</seg>
<seg id="839">The strategy adopted and the new legal regulations can be effective steps to improve the situation.</seg>
<seg id="840">For example, under the new regulations, the contracting authority must justify the effectiveness of the public contract, the determination of the anticipated value of the contract, the adequacy of the requirements for the qualification conditions, the establishment of the basic evaluation criteria and the method of evaluation of the tenders, and properly document and publish everything properly.</seg>
<seg id="841">Recommendations</seg>
<seg id="842">Overall, both the SAO and BRH have a favourable opinion about the ways of implementing EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="843">In practice, their broad application has confirmed that EU competition, equal treatment and transparency requirements provide an appropriate basis for public procurement within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="844">The transnational model, introduced in the EU, can also serve as a basis for similar projects aimed at facilitating and promoting international competition.</seg>
<seg id="845">Taking into account the great potential of material and intangible damage caused as a result of manipulation and corruption in connection with public procurement, both the BRH and the SAO insist that it is the responsibility of contracting authorities to continue measures against corruption and manipulation and to improve them where possible.</seg>
<seg id="846">In particular, organisational structures and procurement procedures should be continuously monitored in terms of weaknesses and risks in order to identify and respond appropriately to the need for corrective action.</seg>
<seg id="847">Compared to practice in Germany, it has emerged that the share of open procurement procedures in the Czech Republic should increase, giving room to competition and substantially reducing the possibility of corrupt behaviour.</seg>
<seg id="848">The award of contracts in parts may also have a positive impact on the price achieved in cases where it is permissible and appropriate for the contracting authority. A higher number of applicants put pressure on the price achieved.</seg>
<seg id="849">The provision of its organisation also has an impact on the conduct of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="850">It is provided by special state organisations in Germany, while in the Czech Republic, with the exception of transport structures, it is organised by the central authorities themselves or through contractual organisations.</seg>
<seg id="851">Both the SAO and BRH want to further develop knowledge in their work where appropriate and address them with their parliament and government beyond their joint project.</seg>
<seg id="852">Moreover, they are convinced that the principles of procurement law and their implementation, as described in this report, will also be of interest at the level of the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI), as these principles and findings are of general importance for effectively tackling corruption and to guarantee that public procurement is awarded in a regime of well-functioning and honest competition and that value for money is achieved.</seg>
<seg id="853">Attachments</seg>
</p>
</doc>
<doc docid="testsuite-segment_65-KA_15_33" genre="news" origlang="cs" sysid="uedin-uedin-transformer-base.snapshot.after-65K-updates">
<p>
<seg id="1">JOINT FINAL REPORT on the results of parallel controls on excise duty management in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint final report</seg>
<seg id="3">May 2017</seg>
<seg id="4">Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="5">Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="6">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="7">The joint report submitted informs about the course and outcome of international cooperation during parallel inspections carried out by the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic, with a focus on the management of excise duties in 2012-2015.</seg>
<seg id="8">Cooperation between the highest audit institutions of both countries was implemented on the basis of a cooperation agreement between the SAO of the Slovak Republic and the SAO of the Czech Republic in the exercise of parallel controls aimed at the administration of excise duties concluded in August 2015.</seg>
<seg id="9">The topic of parallel controls was chosen on the basis of the fact that the two EU Member States are based on common European legislation to see how it is applied at national level, how the excise tax management system is set up and how the systems in Slovakia and the Czech Republic are different.</seg>
<seg id="10">The greatest benefit of the control actions carried out was the exchange of experience, the identification of differences and the identification of good practice.</seg>
<seg id="11">Last but not least, the finding that the international comparability of data on the performance and efficiency of excise duty management was very limited without parallel controls being carried out.</seg>
<seg id="12">Miloslav Kala,</seg>
<seg id="13">Karol Mitrík,</seg>
<seg id="14">President</seg>
<seg id="15">President</seg>
<seg id="16">Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="17">Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="18">on the results of parallel controls of the SPD administration in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="19">Summary and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="20">The legislation on excise duties in the Czech Republic and Slovakia and their administration is in line with EU legislation and significantly exceeds EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="21">Differences were found between the adjustment of excise duties in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic, in the Czech Republic it contributes to the effective administration of excise taxes verification of the economic stability of applicants for the issue of permits and the obligatory marking and colouring of selected mineral oils and some other oils; In the SR, the distribution of control signs is simpler than in the Czech Republic and less burdensome tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the fight against excise tax evasion, supervision of the movement of raw tobacco or tobacco raw material, the implementation of the institute of fuel distributor and the registration of consumer packaging of alcohol has proved to be a good practice in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="23">Revenue from excise duties in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic is growing more slowly than other tax revenues.</seg>
<seg id="24">The EU's targets of reducing labour taxation, introducing environmentally austerity measures and reducing dependence on tobacco and alcohol have not yet been met in the Czech Republic and Slovakia, including because there is no indexation of excise tax rates in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="25">This has the effect of reducing the materiality of excise duties on total tax revenues and, as a result of increasing purchasing power, a real reduction in the tax burden on excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="26">The state has long supported the implementation of environmental measures financially, but these measures have a negative impact on excise revenues, which will need to be replaced in the future by other revenues or by reducing state spending.</seg>
<seg id="27">Administrative expenditures spent on excise tax management in both the Czech Republic and Slovakia have been growing for a long time, mainly due to wage growth, and their efficiency is declining.</seg>
<seg id="28">In the Slovak Republic, this efficiency is also negatively affected by the expenditure on computerising the administration of excise duties (IT expenses) and the expenses incurred on the wages of employees carrying out permanent tax supervision in alcohol tax warehouses.</seg>
<seg id="29">The electronicisation of excise tax management in the SR did not significantly affect the reduction in the number of tax administrations.</seg>
<seg id="30">The SAO of the Czech Republic and the SAO SR recommend to the FŘ SR to reconsider the merits of the exercise of permanent tax supervision in tax warehouses on alcohol.</seg>
<seg id="31">In the Czech Republic, the efficiency of administrative expenditures was influenced by the fact that the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic did not apply procedures in the audited period that would lead to a reduction in the staffing demands of the administration of excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="32">The number of comparable administrative tasks of tax administrators was similar in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic in individual years of the audited period, while the number of comparable tax entities in the Slovak Republic is about a third lower than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="33">Tax administrators in the Slovak Republic carry out administrative tasks mainly in the form of physical exercise of tax supervision, while tax administrators in the Czech Republic emphasize remote supervision and risk analysis.</seg>
