<seg id="1">Report on the results of the parallel control of the value added tax administration carried out in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">The 1977 Lima Declaration underlines that the highest audit institutions (SAI) have the power to audit all public financial operations.</seg>
<seg id="4">The Declaration calls for tax revenues to be checked to the greatest extent possible.</seg>
<seg id="5">The Organisation of the European Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (EUROSAI) considers taxation to be one of the most important parts of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="6">The VI. EUROSAI Congress held in Bonn in 2005 dealt with the audit of public revenue carried out by the SAI.</seg>
<seg id="7">A major step towards optimising SAI control activities is the development of a specific strategy for auditing public revenues.</seg>
<seg id="8">This applies in particular to taxes as the bulkiest source of public revenue, which is most prone to large losses.</seg>
<seg id="9">As national economies become increasingly interconnected and dependent, SAI may be unable to carry out control activities without cooperation with another state's SAI.</seg>
<seg id="10">An example is the audit of internationally organised fraud, which causes substantial losses in the income of many countries.</seg>
<seg id="11">To combat this offence, the responsible authorities need to cooperate with each other.</seg>
<seg id="12">The SAI carrying out checks in this area must be willing to engage in closer cooperation with each other.</seg>
<seg id="13">It was at the EUROSAI Congress in Bonn that the idea of carrying out an inspection of the Value Added Tax Administration (VAT) and the VIES system in the framework of the cooperation of the Supreme Audit Office and the Federal Court of Auditors, the Bundesrechnungshof, arose.</seg>
<seg id="14">Careful preparation followed, with both sides first having to familiarize themselves with the legal environment and procedures for managing VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany.</seg>
<seg id="15">Based on the analysis of this information, a selection of control topics was carried out which was included in the control programme.</seg>
<seg id="16">Achieving an effective and efficient VAT administration is a long-standing problem, and individual states (especially the Member States of the European Union) are looking for solutions to improve, simplify and make the collection of this tax more transparent.</seg>
<seg id="17">We believe that the results of our control can serve not only to improve the work of tax administrators, but also as a basis for a proposal to improve the international information exchange system.</seg>
<seg id="18">Report on the results of parallel checks on the management of value added tax carried out in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="19">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="20">Control number: (CZ) 06/27 (D) VIII 2 – 2005 – 1215</seg>
<seg id="21">Subject-matter of the inspection:</seg>
<seg id="22">(CZ) Value Added Tax Administration after the Czech Republic joined the European Union</seg>
<seg id="23">(D) Examination of administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and Commission Regulation (EC) No 1925/2004</seg>
<seg id="24">Objective of control:</seg>
<seg id="25">(CZ) The aim of the control action in the Czech Republic was to examine the procedure of the financial authorities in the management of value added tax after the integration of the Czech Republic into the single internal market of the European Union (EU) linked to the free movement of goods and services and to examine the use of the VIES system, in particular when checking the application of the right to a value added tax exemption for intracomonity delivery.</seg>
<seg id="26">(D) The aim of the audit was to examine the system of control of intracomonarian value added tax, with a particular focus on administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax under the aforementioned regulations.</seg>
<seg id="27">The result should be a report on weaknesses and recommendations for their elimination.</seg>
<seg id="28">System of exchange of information on value added tax Audit actions were carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the SAO) and the German Bundesrechnungshof (BRH) in mutual cooperation on the basis of a contract concluded between the two audit institutions on 8 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="29">The cooperation focused mainly on the examination of selected commercial transactions carried out between payers from the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the Czech Republic) and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter referred to as the "CFN"), the use of information obtained in the form of international cooperation between tax administrations and the comparison of VAT management systems of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="30">The joint final report on the results of the control actions was prepared within the meaning of European Directive 31 for the implementation of INTOSAI audit standards.</seg>
<seg id="31">The audited period was the period from 1 May 2004 to 31.12.2005.</seg>
<seg id="32">Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions</seg>
<seg id="33">Parallel control in the area of VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of a contract between the two SAI.</seg>
<seg id="34">Outside the main point, exchanges of information under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and Commission Regulation (EC) No 1925/2004 – covered other topics, such as the registration of payers, VAT returns and recapitulative statements, which are closely linked to the main point.</seg>
<seg id="35">In addition, the inspection included the legal situation in the area of international bus passenger transport and a comparison of some statistical data.</seg>
<seg id="36">Comparing the VAT systems of the two countries found differences in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="37">1) VAT registration.</seg>
<seg id="38">While entrepreneurs are registered in Germany regardless of their turnover, in the Czech Republic the primary criterion (among other things) is for registering exceeding the limit set in the VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="39">In the Czech Republic, only one tax identification number is allocated to payers, which they also use in intra-community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="40">In Germany, a VAT number is allocated to payers when registering for VAT, serving only for commercial transactions in the territory of Germany.</seg>
<seg id="41">If a German payer intends to carry out intracomonality transactions, he must apply for the allocation of a special identification number, the so-called VAT ID.</seg>
<seg id="42">As different methods of registration cause problems, conditions should be levelled across the EU (see 4.1).</seg>
<seg id="43">2) International bus passenger transport.</seg>
