<seg id="843">Both Czech payers listed the above mentioned supplies in SH in accordance with the wording of Act No 235/2004 Coll., in force in 2004.</seg>
<seg id="844">By further examining the above transactions, the SAO-controlling group found that in 2004 there were differences between the Czech Republic and Germany in the statutory regulation of the supply or acquisition of electricity.</seg>
<seg id="845">While in the Czech Republic the payers reported the supply of electricity in accordance with the valid wording of Act No. 235/2004 Coll. as an intracommunity supply of goods, in terms of the German legal regulation in force in 2004 it was not an intracomonality acquisition, but a taxable performance with the place of implementation of the fulfilment in the territory of Germany.</seg>
<seg id="846">The difference in statutory regulations in the Czech Republic was eliminated by the adoption of Act No. 635/2004 Coll., amending certain laws in connection with the adoption of the Act on Administrative Fees, effective from 1 January 2005.</seg>
<seg id="847">23. Furthermore, when examining selected intracomonant transactions in cooperation with BRH, it was found that the Czech payer reported an intracomonial delivery to the German payer in the 1st to 4th quarter of 2005 with a total value of 240 411 163 CZK (EUR 871 823) and another Czech payer reported intracomonial delivery to the German payer for the same period with a total value of 263 470 776 CZK (EUR 846 050).</seg>
<seg id="848">According to information provided by the SAO from BRH, both cases involved the supply of electricity.</seg>
<seg id="849">According to the wording of Act No 235/2004 Coll., effective from 1 January 2005, in the case of electricity supply, the place where the acquirer has its registered office, place of business or where it has an establishment for which the goods are delivered.</seg>
<seg id="850">Therefore, Czech payers should not have introduced electricity supplies to SH in 2005.</seg>
<seg id="851">By showing the intracomonality of electricity supply in SH by the two above payers, the VIES data was distorted by a total of CZK 503,881,939 (EUR 16,917,873).</seg>
<seg id="852">Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="853">The cooperation met the objectives of BRH and the SAO.</seg>
<seg id="854">Both SAI received a deeper knowledge of VAT management systems in the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="855">Cooperation has revealed the differences between the two systems and showed that VAT management legislation differs.</seg>
<seg id="856">During parallel checks, suspicious cases of intracomonarian transactions were found.</seg>
<seg id="857">Some of them make sense to subsequently check.</seg>
<seg id="858">Based on the control findings, both SAIs developed recommendations on VAT management.</seg>
<seg id="859">Monitoring these recommendations should also be part of the follow-up.</seg>
<seg id="860">The new experience and knowledge gained through cooperation between the two audit institutions is the basis for the successful implementation of the following VAT administration controls.</seg>
<seg id="861">Communications</seg>
<seg id="862">The report was drawn up in Czech, English and German and signed by the President of the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the President of the Bundesrechnungshof, the Federal Republic of Germany.</seg>
</p>
