<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the outcome of international cooperation in controls on excise duty management between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in 2006</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">The joint report submitted informs about the course and outcome of international cooperation during parallel inspections carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and Najvyšší Control Office of the Slovak Republic, focused on the administration of excise duties in the period after the two countries joined the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="4">The cooperation was implemented on the basis of a cooperation agreement in control activities concluded in February 2006.</seg>
<seg id="5">The topic of parallel checks was chosen in view of the fundamental change in the system of collection of excise duties, which took place in connection with the integration of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic into the internal market of the European Union from 1 May 2004.</seg>
<seg id="6">The functioning of the internal market of the European Union requires the free movement of goods, including excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="7">The basic principle is to allow non-taxable goods to circulate until the date of its final consumption delivery.</seg>
<seg id="8">In accordance with that principle, the new legislation adopted in both countries allows the movement of goods under tax supervision under the suspensive exemption scheme.</seg>
<seg id="9">The system places great demands on the tax authorities and foresees close interaction between the competent administrations of the Member States in the fight against tax fraud in this area.</seg>
<seg id="10">Report on the outcome of international cooperation in controls on excise duty management for the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005 1.</seg>
<seg id="11">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="12">Control number: (Czech Republic) 05/34 (SR) 48/11</seg>
<seg id="13">Subject of control: (Czech Republic) Administration of excise duties (SR) Procedure of colné organs in sprays of spotreb taxes</seg>
<seg id="14">The Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the SAO-ČR) and the Najvyšší Control Office of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the SAO of the SR) concluded on 8 February 2006 the "Contract of Cooperation in Control Activities".</seg>
<seg id="15">The subject of the contract was cooperation during parallel checks carried out by the "Interim Tax Administration", included in the auditing plan of the SAO-ČR for 2005 under No 05/34, and "Control of the procedure of colné organs in sprays of spotrebné taxes", included in the control activity plan of the SAO SR for 2006 under No 48/11.</seg>
<seg id="16">Parallel checks were in the nature of coordinated control.</seg>
<seg id="17">The cooperation consisted of exchanging information that the contracting parties could not obtain when checking the administration of excise duties on the territory of their State and in drawing up a joint final report on the outcome of controls within the meaning of the European implementing directives for the implementation of INTOSAI Audit Standards - Directive 31.</seg>
<seg id="18">In the Czech Republic, the control (hereinafter referred to as the Czech Republic) was carried out by groups inspecting the state budget department and from the territorial unions of Central Bohemia, southern Bohemia, western Bohemia, northwestern Bohemia, northeastern Bohemia, South Moravia, Central Moravia and northern Moravia between 7 February and 2 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">The inspection involved 27 controllers.</seg>
<seg id="20">The audited persons were the General Directorate of Customs (hereinafter referred to as the CD) and 11 tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="21">Within the DGC, 12 selected customs offices out of a total of 54.</seg>
<seg id="22">The audit on the territory of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the "SR") was carried out by the Section of the Financial and Tax Office of the Slovak Republic in cooperation with exposures of the SAO SR Banská Bystrica and Košice at 5 customs offices out of a total of 9 between 13 February and 2 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="23">The inspection involved 8 controllers.</seg>
<seg id="24">The aim of the parallel checks was to examine the procedure of the customs authorities in the administration of excise duties and compliance with the relevant legislation in force in both countries and in the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="25">International cooperation was focused on the procedure of tax administrators in the exercise of supervision of the transport of goods subject to excise duties, in particular the registration of initiated and completed traffic under the conditional exemption regime, and on the exchange of information within the framework of mutual administrative assistance between excise tax administrators of the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="26">2. Management of excise duties</seg>
<seg id="27">The administration of excise duties in the Czech Republic was carried out by the financial authorities until 31 December 2003.</seg>
<seg id="28">Since 1 January 2004, this agenda has been taken over by the customs authorities, which have so far levied excise duty only on importation.</seg>
<seg id="29">In the Czech Republic, mineral oils, alcohol, beer, wine and intermediate products and tobacco products are subject to excise duty.</seg>
<seg id="30">The state budget's revenue from excise duties in the Czech Republic amounted to a total of CZK 82.8 billion in 2004 and 19.5% of the state budget's revenues from taxes and fees.</seg>
<seg id="31">In 2005, the state budget revenue from excise duties amounted to CZK 103.6 billion and the share of state budget revenues from taxes and fees amounting to CZK 460.4 billion was 22.5%.</seg>
<seg id="32">In 2004, the income from excise duty on mineral oils to the State budget was 80% of the total revenue from this tax and in 2005 it was 90.9%.</seg>
<seg id="33">The difference to 100% of CZK 13 billion in 2004 and CZK 6.9 billion in 2005 was the income of the State Fund for Transport Infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="34">The administration of all excise duties in the SR shall be exercised by the customs authorities from 1 May 2004, with the exception of excise duty on mineral oil, which they have been administering since 1 January 2002.</seg>
<seg id="35">Until then, the administration of excise duties was carried out by the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="36">Excise duty in the SR is subject to mineral oil, alcohol, beer, wine and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="37">The revenue of the state budget from excise duties in the SR totalled 43.4 billion Sk in 2004 and in total tax revenues of 209.5 billion Sk, excise duties accounted for 20.7%.</seg>
<seg id="38">In 2005, the state budget revenue from excise duties was 50 billion Sk and total tax revenues of 222.6 billion Sk accounted for 22.5%.</seg>
<seg id="39">Graph 1 — Comparison of revenues of the state budget of the Czech Republic from taxes and fees and tax revenues of the state budget of the Slovak Republic with revenues from excise duties</seg>
<seg id="40">Legislation in both countries is based on European Union rules governing this area, in particular: - Council Directive 92/12/EEC on the general arrangements for the holding, movement and monitoring of products subject to excise duty (hereinafter referred to as "Directive 92/12/EEC), - Council Regulation (EC) No 2073/2004 on administrative cooperation in the field of excise duties (hereinafter referred to as ‘Regulation No 2073/2004’), - Commission Regulation (EEC) No 2719/92 on the accompanying official document for the transport of products subject to excise duty under the suspension of excise duty (hereinafter referred to as ‘Regulation No 2719/92’), - Commission Regulation (EEC) No 3649/92 on a simplified movement for excise duty (hereinafter referred to as Regulation No 2719/92), - Commission Regulation (EEC)</seg>
<seg id="41">The basic legislation governing the issue of excise duties in the Czech Republic is Act No. 353/2003 Coll., on Excise Taxes, as amended, (hereinafter referred to as "Law No. 353/2003 Coll.").</seg>
<seg id="42">When administering excise duties in the SR, customs authorities are bound, inter alia, by the following generally binding legislation: - Act No 98/2004 Z. z. o spotrebne oil tax in the knowledge of non-corporate predtoy (hereinafter referred to as Law No 98/2004 Z. z., - Act No 104/2004 Z. z. z. o spotrebalé tax on wine in the denial of non-corporate predpisov (hereinafter referred to as "Law No 104/2004 Z. z."), - Act No. 105/2004 Z.</seg>
<seg id="43">2.1 Movement of excise goods under a suspensive tax exemption scheme between Member States of the European Union</seg>
<seg id="44">The conditions for the movement of excise goods under the suspension exemption procedure are governed by Directive 92/12/EEC in Title III — Movement of goods from Article 15 to 20.</seg>
<seg id="45">Under those provisions, the transport of those goods may be carried out only by an authorised warehousekeeper, which means a natural or legal person authorised by the competent authorities of a Member State to manufacture, process, store, receive and dispatch products subject to excise duty.</seg>
<seg id="46">A consignee in another Member State may be an authorised warehousekeeper or an economic operator without the status of an authorised warehousekeeper, but who may not, under a suspensive exemption scheme, store or dispatch them further.</seg>
<seg id="47">The authorised warehousekeeper in the Czech Republic and Slovakia means the operator of a tax warehouse, the economic operator is the beneficiary for the repeated or one-off acceptance of products subject to excise duty.</seg>
<seg id="48">Under Directive 92/12/EEC, the transport of excise products subject to excise duty is only possible with an accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="49">The accompanying document shall be issued by the consignor before the commencement of the service in four copies, unless the competent authorities of the Member State of dispatch request a further copy.</seg>
<seg id="50">2.2 Procedure for the start and termination of the transport of goods under the conditional exemption procedure between the Czech Republic and Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="51">Transport from the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="52">The procedure for the commencement of transport is governed by the provisions of Section 25(3) of Act No 353/2003 Coll., which states, among other things:</seg>
<seg id="53">‘The operator of the tax warehouse shall, before commencing the transport of the selected products, inform the customs office which is the place competent for the tax warehouse from which transport is to be commenced;</seg>
<seg id="54">transport of selected products can only be initiated with the consent of this customs office.</seg>
<seg id="55">The customs office shall give its consent to the transport of the selected products without delay after the condition of securing the tax is met ..."</seg>
<seg id="56">A freight forwarder in the Czech Republic may commence the transport of all types of products subject to excise duty only with the consent of the locally competent customs office.</seg>
<seg id="57">The customs office shall give its consent to the commencement of transport only if the tax is provided for the amount of tax attributable to the products transported.</seg>
<seg id="58">Before commencing the transport, the sender is obliged to prepare an accompanying document in five copies.</seg>
<seg id="59">On the accompanying document, the customs office shall indicate its consent to the commencement of transport.</seg>
<seg id="60">Production No 1 shall be retained by the consignor, copy Nos 2, 3, and 4 shall be surrendered by the consignor to the carrier and copy No 5 shall be retained by the customs office authorising the transport.</seg>
<seg id="61">Under the Slovak legislation, the recipient in SR will keep copy No 2 of the accompanying document. On the copies Nos 3 and 4, they shall acknowledge receipt of the products and submit the two copies to the competent customs office locally.</seg>
<seg id="62">Production No 3 confirmed by the customs office shall send to the consignor no later than the 15th day of the month following the calendar month in which he accepted the products.</seg>
<seg id="63">Production No 4 shall be retained by the customs office of the consignee.</seg>
<seg id="64">Transport is terminated by the acceptance of products by the recipient.</seg>
<seg id="65">The release of the tax security will be decided by the customs office in the Czech Republic, which authorised the start of transport, within 5 working days of the submission of copy No 3 of the accompanying document, which is confirmed by the beneficiary and the Slovak customs office.</seg>
<seg id="66">Chart No. 2 — Circulation of the accompanying transport document initiated in the Czech Republic and terminated in the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="67">Transport from SR</seg>
<seg id="68">The procedure for transporting alcohol and tobacco products from the Slovak Republic to another Member State of the European Union has been amended by 31 December 2005 as follows:</seg>
<seg id="69">Under Paragraph 26(4) of Law 105/2004 Z.</seg>
<seg id="70">‘Pri preprave liehu from the tax warehouse into the tax warehouse of the territory to the tax warehouse but to the authorized referee, or to the tax splnomocnenc in inom memberskom is the odosielatel’ (supplier’) obligatory in the beginning of the preparation to send the kópiu of the first diel of the sprievodní document electronically or fax to the Colný úradu Poprad; túto kópiu is obligatory sowing and the colny mouth of the font into the piatich working days from the dauňa zaratia pre-treatment."</seg>
<seg id="71">Under Paragraph 22(4) of Law No 106/2004 Z.</seg>
<seg id="72">‘Pri preprave tabak manufactories from the tax warehouse into the tax warehouse of the territory to the tax warehouse but to the authorized prime minister, or to the tax splnomocnenc in the inom membership is the odosielatel' (supplier’) obligatory in the beginning of the preparation to send a cubicum of the first diel of the sprievodate document electronically or fax to Colný úrad; túto kópiu is obligatory sowing and the colny mouth of the song najneskor to the piatich working days from the dña beginatia pre-treatment."</seg>
<seg id="73">In the transport of other products subject to excise duty (mineral oil, wine and beer) during the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005 (hereinafter referred to as the ‘controlled period’), the taxpayer was under no obligation to notify the Customs Office of Poprad or the competent customs office of the commencement of services under the suspensive regime.</seg>
<seg id="74">The tax administrator only became aware of the transport of these products during a local investigation or during a tax inspection from the accompanying documents and from the tax entity's accounting documents.</seg>
<seg id="75">The consignor in SR is obliged to prepare an accompanying document in four copies before the start of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="76">Production No 1 shall be retained by the consignor (when transporting alcohol and tobacco products, he shall send a copy of copy No 1 electronically or by fax to the Customs Office of Poprad and to the competent customs office).</seg>
<seg id="77">Production Nos 2, 3 and 4 accompanies the goods transported.</seg>
<seg id="78">According to the Czech legislation, the recipient in the Czech Republic will keep copy No 2 of the accompanying document issued by the consignor in the Slovak Republic and confirm the acceptance of the products on the copies No 3 and 4.</seg>
<seg id="79">The confirmed copy Nos 3 and 4 will be sent no later than the first working day after the end of the transport to the locally competent customs office in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="80">The customs office shall retain copy No 4 and copy No 3 to verify the correctness and validity shall be returned to the consignee.</seg>
<seg id="81">The beneficiary shall send a certified copy No 3 no later than the following working day after receiving it to the Sender to SR.</seg>
<seg id="82">Transport in the SR is considered to be completed on the day of receipt of the products by the beneficiary.</seg>
<seg id="83">The end of the transport is demonstrated by the consignor by submitting copy No 3 of the accompanying document confirmed by the recipient and the tax administrator in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="84">Graph No. 3 — Circulation of the accompanying document for transport (iron and tobacco products) initiated in Slovakia and terminated in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="85">In 2006, amendments to all laws on excise duties were gradually adopted in the Slovak Republic, according to which the consignor of goods under the suspension arrangement is obliged to send a copy of copy No 1 of the accompanying document electronically or by fax to the local competent consignor before the commencement of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="86">A document proving the cessation of the transport of alcohol and tobacco products is the copy No 3 of the accompanying document confirmed by the beneficiary and its competent tax authority.</seg>
<seg id="87">A document proving the cessation of transport of mineral oils, wine and beer is copy No 3 confirmed by the recipient.</seg>
<seg id="88">Confirmation by the tax administrator of another Member State of receipt of those goods by the consignee shall be required if that controller is required, under the legislation of the competent Member State, to certify copy No 3 of the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="89">2.3 Records of operations initiated and terminated by customs authorities in the Czech Republic and Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="90">In order to monitor the transport of goods under a conditional exemption regime between Member States of the European Union, a single electronic system is not in place.</seg>
<seg id="91">Decision 1152/2003/EC of the European Parliament and of the Council of 16 June 2003 on the establishment of an electronic system for the transport and monitoring of products subject to excise duty requires Member States and the European Commission to establish an electronic system (Excise Movement and Control System) from 1 July 2009 allowing excise tax administrations in each Member State to obtain real-time information on the carriage of goods.</seg>
<seg id="92">The system will allow the electronic transmission of accompanying documents, which are currently only used in paper form, and will contribute to simplifying the movement of goods under the conditional exemption regime and to ensuring a more effective control of the movement of untaxed products across all Member States.</seg>
<seg id="93">This system will include national databases for each Member State's transport.</seg>
<seg id="94">The Customs Administration of the Czech Republic records all transport initiated and terminated on the territory of the Czech Republic in the module Evidence of selected products (hereinafter referred to as "EVV").</seg>
<seg id="95">All customs authorities in the Czech Republic have access to the system online.</seg>
<seg id="96">In the case of transport carried out only on the territory of the Czech Republic, tax authorities may obtain information about the start or end of the service immediately after the registration of the accompanying document by the customs office to EVV.</seg>
<seg id="97">The customs office shall release the security of the tax on the transported products provided by the consignor at the time of registration by the customs office of the competent beneficiary.</seg>
<seg id="98">Customs authorities in the SR use a database based on SysNed's application software, which ensures the automation of their activities in the management of excise duties and communication with European Union systems.</seg>
<seg id="99">By registering a tax warehouse, a tax warehouse operator or an authorised recipient in SysNed's application software, this figure is automatically transferred to the "System for Exchange of Excise Data" database (SEED).</seg>
<seg id="100">3. Preparation and conduct of cooperation</seg>
<seg id="101">The first coordination meeting of representatives of the SAO-ČR and representatives of the SAO SR, at which the specific cooperation procedure for the implementation of parallel controls in the field of excise duties was discussed, took place in January 2006.</seg>
<seg id="102">The two sides became acquainted with the legislation on excise duties and the organisation of excise tax administrations in both states.</seg>
<seg id="103">Particular attention was paid to the procedure of the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and the SR in authorising or in the initiation and termination of the transport of products subject to excise duty under the conditional exemption regime and the exchange of information between excise tax administrations of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="104">At the meeting, it was agreed that the Czech and Slovak sides would: - process the total data on the quantities of products subject to excise duty transported from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic and vice versa, the transport of which started in the audited period, - compare the data on mineral oil transport - Combined Nomenclature code 2710 and 2711 and alcohol - the Combined Nomenclature code 2207 and 2208 under the conditional exemption scheme initiated in the Czech Republic and terminated in the Slovak Republic and vice versa in the months of November 2004 and September 2005.</seg>
<seg id="105">During the inspections, the periods examined were extended by the months of October and November 2005 and the transport of tobacco products under the suspensive exemption scheme was also subject to scrutiny in these months.</seg>
<seg id="106">Tables 1 and 2 show the total quantity of products subject to excise duty which were carried under the suspensive tax exemption scheme between Czech and Slovak tax entities during the audited period.</seg>
<seg id="107">4. Comparison of registrations of goods under suspension of tax</seg>
<seg id="108">The SAO-ČR handed over to the Slovak side a database of transport terminated in the Czech Republic, which contained a total of 5 876 items listed on the accompanying documents, of which 5,738 items related to mineral oils, 134 items of alcohol and 4 items of tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="109">The SAO handed over to the Czech side a database of transport terminated in Slovakia, which contained a total of 3,319 items listed on the accompanying documents, of which 696 related to mineral oil, 2 066 items of alcohol and 557 items of tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="110">The SAO-ČR compared the data on the traffic listed in the register of initiated traffic in the Czech Republic with data on completed traffic registered in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="111">The results of the comparison are presented in Table 3.</seg>
<seg id="112">Data on transport in the months of November 2004 and September 2005 compared the SAO-ČR with the database of the Slovak customs administration, which the SAO handed over to him at the beginning of the audit.</seg>
<seg id="113">The database did not contain data allowing reliable transport to be agreed and therefore only 63% of the commenced services were assigned.</seg>
<seg id="114">Individual services were assigned according to multiple data, e.g. the consignor, the recipient, the date of transport, the quantity of products transported.</seg>
<seg id="115">Data on traffic initiated in the Czech Republic and terminated in the Slovak Republic in the months of October and November 2005 compared the SAO-ČR with the database of the Slovak customs administration, which contained all data according to the accompanying documents, on the basis of which 93% of the commenced services were clearly assigned.</seg>
<seg id="116">In the database of the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic, data on the amount of mineral oils were given in litres or tonnes depending on the type of mineral oil.</seg>
<seg id="117">The amount of alcohol was in most cases mentioned in litres, which, however, could be converted into litres of absolute alcohol based on the database of that percentage alcohol content.</seg>
<seg id="118">The amount of tobacco products was shown in pieces, in thousands of pieces and kilograms depending on the type of tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="119">For traffic initiated in the Czech Republic, the termination of which could not be reliably verified in the Slovak database or where the information about the transported quantity of products was not met, the accompanying documents were checked.</seg>
<seg id="120">The control was subjected to accompanying documents for 487 transport of alcohol, mineral oils and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="121">The examination of these documents was carried out at the customs offices at which the SAO-ČR carried out checks.</seg>
<seg id="122">For services authorised by other customs offices, the accompanying documents were requested through the DGC.</seg>
<seg id="123">The Czech side asked the Slovak side to verify the implementation of 141 traffic, for which the customs authorities in the Czech Republic did not substantiate the confirmed copy No 3 of the accompanying document, or did not agree with the quantity of products listed in the database.</seg>
<seg id="124">Furthermore, data on the services registered in the Slovak database were handed over to the Slovak side, which, however, did not contain the database of transport of the Czech customs administration.</seg>
<seg id="125">The SAO SR found 95 traffic in the Slovak Customs Administration database.</seg>
<seg id="126">The verification of the remaining 46 services was requested by the locally competent customs authorities, who proved their termination with copies of the accompanying documents.</seg>
<seg id="127">The Slovak side forwarded to the Czech side copies of the accompanying documents, on the basis of which transport was also identified in the Czech database, with the exception of transport carried out by two Czech tax entities, which were not found in the Czech database of initiated traffic.</seg>
<seg id="128">A check of these cases was found to be:</seg>
<seg id="129">- 11 transport of alcohol was registered in the Slovak transport database in the total amount of 276.7 litres of alcohol carried out by the Czech tax entity in 2004 and 20 transport of alcohol in a total amount of 404.66 litres of alcohol carried out in 2005.</seg>
<seg id="130">The SAO-ČR found that it was a transport of taxed products, the start of which the sender does not need the consent of the tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="131">The freight forwarder informed the tax administrator in writing about the start of the service. He carried out the transport on the basis of accompanying documents used for the transport of products under the suspensive exemption scheme;</seg>
<seg id="132">- a total of 94 transport of mineral oils, Combined Nomenclature code 2710 11 21, totalling 173 thousand litres realized by the Czech tax entity between September 2004 and December 2005 were registered in the Slovak transport database.</seg>
<seg id="133">The SAO-ČR found that between May 2004 and June 2005, the tax entity carried out transport of 102,000 litres of untaxed mineral oils without proper authorisation.</seg>
<seg id="134">The tax entity held a special authorisation for the receipt and use of products exempt, on the basis of which it could supply untaxed products only to the holder of the same authorisation.</seg>
<seg id="135">He did not notify the opening of the transport authority in the Czech Republic and did not provide a tax security of CZK 1,207,680.</seg>
<seg id="136">Between July 2005 and December 2005, the tax entity delivered 71,000 litres of taxed mineral oils to the territory of the SR. Even in these cases, he did not comply with the legal obligation by not announcing the opening of the transport office to the customs office.</seg>
<seg id="137">The transport of products put into free tax circulation on the tax territory of the Czech Republic to another Member State may be initiated by the consignor in the Czech Republic without the consent of the customs office, but he is obliged to inform the customs office in writing before the commencement of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="138">A tax entity taking products put into free tax circulation in another Member State is obliged to report quantities and ensure tax before they are withdrawn.</seg>
<seg id="139">Products may be transported only with a simplified accompanying document, the particulars of which are governed by Regulation No 3649/92.</seg>
<seg id="140">This Regulation also accepts the use of the accompanying transport document under the suspensive exemption scheme, which must, however, clearly indicate that it is a ‘simplified accompanying document for the purposes of tax control (excise products)’.</seg>
<seg id="141">The same rules on transport and acceptance of products put into free tax circulation in another Member State also apply in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="142">In those cases, the tax authorities transported the products put into free tax circulation with the accompanying transport document under the suspensive exemption scheme, the 3rd and 4th copy of which the recipient submitted to the tax administrator in the SR for verification.</seg>
<seg id="143">The customs authorities in the SR registered these services in the transport database under the suspensive exemption scheme, as the accompanying documents did not state that it was a simplified accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="144">The SAO SR compared the database of transport of the Czech customs administration with the database of transport of the Slovak customs administration and found:</seg>
<seg id="145">- in the databases the quantity of products transported was reported inconsistently, e.g. mineral oil was given in litres, in hectolitres or in kilograms; alcohol was given in litres or litres of alcohol, making it more difficult to compare the quantity of goods transported,</seg>
<seg id="146">- the amount of alcohol transported in the invoices did not coincide with the amount recorded in the databases,</seg>
<seg id="147">- not all related invoices listed in the databases,</seg>
<seg id="148">- two transport of alcohol from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic were registered in the database of the Slovak customs administration carried out in November 2004 in a total volume of 47,237 litres of alcohol, which were not in the database of the Czech customs administration.</seg>
<seg id="149">The Slovak side handed over copies of the accompanying documents to the Czech side.</seg>
<seg id="150">5. International exchange of information between the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="151">The conditions for cooperation between the administrative authorities of the Member States responsible for excise duty management were governed by 30 June 2005 by Council Directive 77/799/EEC on mutual assistance between the competent authorities of the Member States in the field of direct taxation, certain excise duties and taxes on insurance premiums.</seg>
<seg id="152">On 1 July 2005, Regulation No 2073/2004, which lays down rules and procedures allowing the competent authorities of the Member States of the European Union to cooperate and exchange information necessary for the correct assessment of excise duties, entered into force.</seg>
<seg id="153">Each Member State shall designate a central liaison office which shall ensure contacts with other Member States in the field of excise duty management and is responsible for exchanging information on the movement of excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="154">In the Czech Republic, for securing the exchange of information in the field of excise duties between the Member States of the European Union, a paper was set up at the DGC "Excise Liaison Office" (hereinafter referred to as "ELO ČR").</seg>
<seg id="155">The safeguarding of tasks related to the management of systems for the control of the movement of excise goods (SEED, MVS, EWSE) and the exchange of information under mutual administrative assistance between the Member States of the European Union and the SR were carried out with effect from 1 May 2004 by the ELO at the Customs Office of Poprad.</seg>
<seg id="156">With effect from 1 July 2005, the tasks of the ELO Office (based in Poprad) of the Excise Taxation Department of the Customs Directorate of the Slovak Republic (ELO SR) fulfil the tasks of the ELO.</seg>
<seg id="157">Pursuant to the provisions of Article 3(3) of Regulation No 2073/2004, the central liaison office is responsible, inter alia, for - the exchange of data held in the SEED electronic register, - the Early Warning System Excise (EWSE), - requests for verification of the movement of excise goods sent to or received by the Movement Verification System (MVS).</seg>
<seg id="158">The content, scope and functions of SEED, EWSE and MVS are governed by Articles 22, 23 and 24 of Regulation No 2073/2004.</seg>
<seg id="159">SEED - a system for the exchange of information on tax entities trading in excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="160">The system is made up of national registers of excise payers and allows tax administrations in the territory of the European Union to determine whether products subject to excise duty are traded by a person entitled to do so.</seg>
<seg id="161">Each national register shall be made available to the competent authorities of the other Member States for excise purposes only.</seg>
<seg id="162">The central liaison office of each Member State shall ensure that persons involved in the movement of excise goods within the territory of the European Union can obtain confirmation of the information stored in that database.</seg>
<seg id="163">In accordance with Section 41 of Act No 98/2004 Z. z., § 39 of Act No 104/2004 Z. z., with Section 46 of Act No 105/2004 Z. z., § 40 of Act No 106/2004 Z. z. and with § 39 of Act No 107/2004 Z. ELO SR maintains an electronic database containing a register of tax warehouse operators, authorised beneficiaries and tax warehouses - SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="164">The customs authorities in the SR contribute to the SEED database by registering a tax warehouse, a tax warehouse operator or an authorised recipient in the SysNed application software, which is automatically linked to the ELO SR.</seg>
<seg id="165">For example, if a new tax warehouse operator, an authorised recipient or a tax warehouse is registered in the SysNed database, they automatically transfer the related data to the SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="166">The SAO of the SR found that the exchange of SEED databases between the customs administration of the Slovak Republic and the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic took place in the audited period usually once a month, exceptionally several times a month.</seg>
<seg id="167">SR Customs accepted 22 SEED files and sent 25 SEED files.</seg>
<seg id="168">The data to the SEED database in the Czech Republic are transferred from the national register, in which all persons authorised to dispose of products subject to excise duty and issued authorizations to deal with these products are registered.</seg>
<seg id="169">Individual customs offices in the Czech Republic do not have access to the international SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="170">Applications by customs authorities to provide information from the SEED database of other member countries are obtained only through the ELO CR.</seg>
<seg id="171">EWSE - an early warning system aimed at controlling the transport of excise goods through which the transport of risky consignments is announced.</seg>
<seg id="172">A risk consignment is considered to be, on the one hand, the transport of certain products subject to excise duty in quantities exceeding the limits set by the European Commission Regulation and, on the other hand, to transport assessed as risky by the tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="173">The exchange of information is realized in two forms:</seg>
<seg id="174">- information - is sent when the limits are exceeded,</seg>
<seg id="175">- alert message - is sent if the transport of goods is assessed as risky.</seg>
<seg id="176">When assessing the level of risk of an ELO SR consignment, it uses the SEED database to send a warning message, on the basis of which it checks the data contained in the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="177">In the event that the SEED database does not agree with the data in the accompanying document (for example, it does not match the registration number of the recipient of the goods or the registered office of the consignee), the ELO SR shall draw up a warning report sent to the ELO of the Member State of the recipient of the goods.</seg>
<seg id="178">In drawing up the reports, the ELO follows the regulations of the Tax and Customs Commission CED 317 and CED 457, which determine, among other things, the type and quantity of goods in the relevant units of measurement for the preparation of explanatory and warning reports.</seg>
<seg id="179">In the audited period of ELO SR, the ELO sent one warning message to the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="180">In the Czech Republic, information about started transport of products in quantities exceeding set limits is generated automatically when entering data from the accompanying document into the database when approving transport.</seg>
<seg id="181">If the tax administrator in the Czech Republic evaluates the consignment as risky on the basis of its own analysis, it will prepare a so-called warning message, which it will send through the ELO ČR to the relevant Member State.</seg>
<seg id="182">In 2005, the ELO CR sent two warning messages to the ELO SR.</seg>
<seg id="183">The MVS - the system for controlling the movement of goods - makes it possible, through MVS requests, to control individual transport services of products subject to excise duty as well as the control of a specified route of transport between the entities listed in the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="184">The exchange of information shall take place on the basis of a request in which the ELO of the sending country specifies its requirements.</seg>
<seg id="185">The system shall be used in particular in cases where the consignor takes receipt of the confirmed copy No 3 of the accompanying document and requires, for example, the refund of excise duty and in cases where the data contained in the accompanying document cannot be verified in the international SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="186">In the audited period ELO SR sent 33 MVS applications to the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="187">ELO ČR sent ELO SR 25 MVS applications.</seg>
<seg id="188">Customs authorities in the Czech Republic most often examined the data contained in the accompanying documents, in particular the quantities of products received or dispatched or whether the consignor of the products listed in the accompanying document is entitled to dispose of the products subject to excise duty, unless this fact could be verified in the international SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="189">The accepted MVS applications were forwarded in both countries to the customs offices locally competent for the recipients or consignors of products subject to excise duty.</seg>
<seg id="190">The customs authorities examined the required data and reported the outcome of the investigation through the ELO to the other member country.</seg>
<seg id="191">6. Summary</seg>
<seg id="192">The cooperation of the SAO-ČR and the SAO SR made it possible to compare the basic legislation governing the area of excise duties in both states, the procedure of the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in initiating and terminating the transport of products under the conditional exemption regime between the two states, the registration of these services and further compare the exchange of information between customs authorities within the framework of international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="193">6.1 Compared to the legislation governing excise duties in the Czech Republic and Slovakia, differences were found:</seg>
<seg id="194">(a) in the procedure of tax entities and tax administrations in initiating the transport of products under the suspensive exemption scheme.</seg>
<seg id="195">The transport of products under the suspensive exemption scheme can only be initiated by the taxpayer in the Czech Republic with the consent of the tax administrator, who authorises the commencement of transport on condition that the transported products were provided with a tax security equal to the tax attributable to them.</seg>
<seg id="196">The start of the transport of products under the suspension exemption scheme in the SR is not subject to the authorisation of the tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="197">In the audited period, the taxpayer was obliged to notify the tax administrator of the start of the transport of alcohol and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="198">He was able to commence the transport of mineral oils, beer and wine without informing the tax authorities of this fact.</seg>
<seg id="199">In 2006, amendments to all laws on excise duties were gradually adopted in the Slovak Republic, according to which the consignor of goods under the conditional exemption procedure is obliged to send a copy of copy No 1 of the accompanying document electronically or by fax to the customs office, which is the locally competent consignor;</seg>
<seg id="200">(b) within the time limits for dispatch of copy No 3 of the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="201">The beneficiary in the Czech Republic is obliged to send copy 3 and 4 of the accompanying document to the tax administrator for verification at the latest on the following working day after the end of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="202">The verified copy No 3 shall be sent to the consignor no later than the following working day after receiving it from the tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="203">The consignee in SR is obliged to send the consignor of the products copy No 3 confirmed by the tax authority and the recipient of the products no later than the 15th day of the month following the month in which he received the goods.</seg>
<seg id="204">6.2. Customs authorities in both Slovakia and the Czech Republic keep electronic records of transport of products under the conditional exemption regime.</seg>
<seg id="205">The content and method of keeping this register is not regulated by legislation in the Czech Republic or Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="206">Customs authorities in both countries shall enter into the register all data from the accompanying documents on the basis of which transport is carried out.</seg>
<seg id="207">In order to monitor the transport of goods under a conditional tax exemption regime between Member States of the European Union, there is currently no single electronic system that allows excise tax administrations in individual Member States to obtain real-time information on the carriage of goods.</seg>
<seg id="208">Pursuant to Decision 1152/2003/EC of the European Parliament and of the Council of 16 June 2003, an electronic system for monitoring the transport of products subject to excise duty is foreseen from 1 July 2009.</seg>
<seg id="209">On the basis of the cooperation agreement in the control activities, the Czech side handed over to the Slovak side a database of transport of products under the conditional exemption regime initiated in Slovakia and terminated in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="210">The database contained 5 876 items relating to transported mineral oils, alcohol and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="211">The Slovak side forwarded to the Czech side a database of transport of products under the conditional exemption regime initiated in the Czech Republic and terminated in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="212">The database contained 3,319 items relating to transported mineral oils, alcohol and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="213">The Czech side compared the data on the traffic listed in the register of initiated traffic in the Czech Republic with the registration of traffic terminated in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="214">The Slovak side compared the data on the transport of goods under the conditional exemption regime initiated in the Slovak Republic and terminated in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="215">The comparison of the data was made more difficult by the fact that the quantity of goods transported was not stated uniformly in the databases.</seg>
<seg id="216">In cases where it was not possible to clearly attribute the data on individual transports in the two registers, the accompanying documents was checked and the breach of the suspensive exemption scheme and cases of tax evasion were not found.</seg>
<seg id="217">Based on the findings of parallel checks, it can be concluded that Member States can obtain valuable information from the register of transport to improve the management of excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="218">The establishment of an electronic system for the transport and control of excise goods within the meaning of Decision No 1152/2003/EC of the European Parliament and of the Council shall allow electronic transmission of the accompanying document and more effective control of movements under the conditional exemption regime within the territory of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="219">Communications</seg>
<seg id="220">This report was prepared in Czech, English and Slovak.</seg>
<seg id="221">The report was signed by the chairman of Najýššie's Audit Office of the Slovak Republic and the President of the Supreme Audit Office, Czech Republic.</seg>
</p>
