<doc docid="testsuite-segment_65-KA_09_11_OCR" genre="news" origlang="en" sysid="uedin-uedin-transformer-base.snapshot.after-65K-updates">
<p>
<seg id="1">Value Added Tax Administration in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Report on the results of the follow-up</seg>
<seg id="3">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="4">Taxes generally represent a key source of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="5">It is therefore self-evident that the supreme Audit Institutions (SAI) should concentrate their attention on this area.</seg>
<seg id="6">Examples include value added tax fraud (VAT).</seg>
<seg id="7">For their case, a loss of EUR 100 billion is estimated annually in the European Union (EU).</seg>
<seg id="8">Already in 2005, the participants of the VI Congress of EUROSAI in Bonn agreed on the need for very close cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="9">As part of this cooperation, SAI can exchange control procedures, find the best solutions, etc.</seg>
<seg id="10">VAT is a very suitable area for control cooperation, as it is the only tax harmonised within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="11">The Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (hereinafter also the SAO) and the Federal Court of Auditors (Bundesrechnungshof, as well as theBRH) carried out the first parallel VAT control action in 2006.</seg>
<seg id="12">The report was published in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="13">As fraudulent VAT negotiations are not limited to a single country but is widespread across the EU, close cooperation between the SAI is needed to ensure a comprehensive evaluation of the actions taken to address the problem.</seg>
<seg id="14">The two SAI therefore decided to further develop cooperation in this area and carried out a subsequent parallel control.</seg>
<seg id="15">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="16">Control number: (CZ) 09/11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892</seg>
<seg id="17">Subject of the audit: (CZ) Value Added Tax Administration (D) Bilateral audit with the SAO (follow-up)</seg>
<seg id="18">Objective of control:</seg>
<seg id="19">(CZ) The aim of the audit was to examine the procedure of the financial authorities in the VAT administration, in particular to verify the procedure for dealing with selected cases of commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter referred to as "Germany") and to examine the procedures of the tax administrations of both countries in the framework of international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="20">(D) The audit action was proposed to evaluate the measures taken by the tax administration to implement the recommendations issued by the SAO and BRH.</seg>
<seg id="21">The intention was also to cover other areas related to VAT.</seg>
<seg id="22">The resulting control findings were intended to compare with the proven practice found (if any).</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited period covered the years 2006 to 2008, in case of factual context as well as the preceding and following periods, until the end of the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="24">2. Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions</seg>
<seg id="25">The subsequent inspection of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two SAIs.</seg>
<seg id="26">During previous parallel inspections, suspicious cases of intracomonarian transactions were detected.</seg>
<seg id="27">Some of them required further screening.</seg>
<seg id="28">On the basis of the control findings, the two SAI formulated a VAT administration recommendation.</seg>
<seg id="29">The follow-up control action carried out was used to evaluate the measures taken in response to these recommendations and to examine selected suspicious cases.</seg>
<seg id="30">The audit also focused, for example, on selected cases of high-risk intracomonality transactions, mutual assistance in debt recovery and the implementation of VAT controls for large tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="31">When checking the VAT administration in selected areas in both countries, the auditors reached the following checks:</seg>
<seg id="32">1. Recommendations from previous control</seg>
<seg id="33">• Recommendation 1: Conditions for registering payers should be harmonised within the EU</seg>
<seg id="34">In previous parallel checks, the comparison of VAT registration systems in both countries identified differences.</seg>
<seg id="35">As different types of registration cause problems, both SAIs recommended harmonising the conditions for registering payers within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="36">This recommendation was made at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="37">The draft amendment to Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 on administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax and repealing Regulation (EEC) No 218/92 (hereinafter referred to as "Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003) called for the extension of existing databases within the EU, including a database of tax identification numbers of VAT payers.</seg>
<seg id="38">He also adjusted common standards for the registration and deregistration of tax payers.</seg>
<seg id="39">The SAI expected EU Member States to agree on appropriate standards to support their decision to exclude unreliable traders from the VAT system as quickly as possible.</seg>
<seg id="40">However, the latest version of that document, agreed by EU Member States under ECOFIN, does not already contain the issue.</seg>
<seg id="41">Both SAI regret notes that the idea of common minimum standards has been abandoned.</seg>
<seg id="42">However, they continue to see this intention as a relevant prevention tool in the fight against fraudulent VAT practices.</seg>
<seg id="43">• Recommendation 2: Monthly submission of recapitulative statements</seg>
<seg id="44">As part of international cooperation, the previous control action recommended that all EU countries introduce a monthly deadline for submitting recapitulative statements, allowing for a more timely examination of the values of intracomonality transactions.</seg>
<seg id="45">Council Directive 2008/117/EC amending Directive 2006/112/EC on the common system of value added tax to combat intra-Community tax evasion limits to one month.</seg>
<seg id="46">In the Czech Republic, this measure was implemented through the Value Added Tax Act with effect from 1 January 2010, implemented in Germany from 1 July 2010.</seg>
<seg id="47">In Germany, the obligation to submit recapitulative statements was not introduced monthly within the deadline, in accordance with the EU regulations in force, while in the Czech Republic it was.</seg>
<seg id="48">• Recommendation 3: Comparison of data in VAT returns and recapitulative statements in Germany to achieve greater reliability of VIES data and consideration of linking the two VAT return systems and for recapitulative statements</seg>
<seg id="49">The German tax administration accepted the BRH recommendations and set up a working group to explore possible solutions.</seg>
<seg id="50">Work is still ongoing and BRH will closely monitor further developments.</seg>
<seg id="51">• Recommendation 4: Sharing successful criteria, components and approaches of a risk management system at EU level Based on the results of the previous control action, both SAI agreed that an effective risk management system could not be developed by just one Member State.</seg>
<seg id="52">Successful criteria, components and approaches of the risk management system need to be exchanged and implemented in individual EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="53">If this is not the case, the perpetrators of fraudulent activity will be chosen by the Member State with the weakest risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="54">The check found that our two Member States use different risk management systems that have their strengths and weaknesses.</seg>
<seg id="55">In this area, the SAO audited the EUROCANET system, which allows the exchange of information within the EU, while BRH concentrated on German participation in the so-called risk management platform.</seg>
<seg id="56">2. Follow-up of selected cases of intracomonality transactions</seg>
<seg id="57">In the course of the previous audit, commercial transactions were jointly examined for which there were doubts about their execution or irregularities in the reporting of commercial transactions in tax returns or recapitulative statements by the tax payer from both countries.</seg>
<seg id="58">Both SAI selected nine cases for subsequent inspection, which included the intracomonality movement of goods between the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="59">Checks by the tax authorities of the countries concerned were not concluded at the date of completion of our previous joint control operation.</seg>
<seg id="60">The subsequent inspection operation verified that most of the tax proceedings in connection with the mentioned selected cases of commercial transactions between payers from the Czech Republic and Germany had been closed and that adequate measures had been taken by the tax administration of the Czech Republic or Germany (e.g. additional VAT collection or the avoidance of input tax refund).</seg>
<seg id="61">3. Checking selected cases of risky intracomonant transactions</seg>
<seg id="62">High risk cases of intracomonality transactions carried out by EU payers that have been included in EUROCANET have been selected for inspection.</seg>
<seg id="63">EUROCANET is a tool for detecting risky tax payers within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="64">The participation of Member States in this system is voluntary.</seg>
<seg id="65">The Czech Republic is an active participant in EUROCANET, while Germany has passive status.</seg>
<seg id="66">It is unsatisfactory for an active participant in the scheme if some Member States refuse to participate actively.</seg>
<seg id="67">Given the fact that the German tax authorities were not involved in the exchange of data in EUROCANET, it was not possible to obtain any information on which suppliers with German VAT ID were assessed as risky.</seg>
<seg id="68">As part of the audit, the SAO found both cases of normal commercial transactions and cases suspected of involvement in carousel transactions or fraudulent VAT behaviour.</seg>
<seg id="69">Tax administrators have limited opportunities to control risky transactions, especially as regards so-called missing traders, and mere physical examination of documents can hardly prove any fraudulent conduct to the taxpayer.</seg>
<seg id="70">A similar situation for tax administrations occurs when imports and exports to third countries are linked to intracomonity carousel shops.</seg>
<seg id="71">In such cases, it would be appropriate to ensure greater cooperation between customs and financial authorities in order to identify goods and irregularities in the transport documentation, as well as to monitor their physical movements within the EU towards the end consumer.</seg>
<seg id="72">Germany, like some other countries, is hesitant to actively engage in EUROCANET due to the lack of a sufficient legal basis.</seg>
<seg id="73">In Germany, other tools are being used to detect risky tax payers, which until now have worked well for the German tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="74">In this area, experience between EU Member States needs to be communicated and exchanged.</seg>
<seg id="75">The Council of the EU has reached political agreement on the draft regulation amending Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003.</seg>
<seg id="76">Its main innovation lies in the creation of the EUROFISC network.</seg>
<seg id="77">The experience gained so far in the use of EUROCANET should be the basis for the creation of this new network to combat VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="78">4. Mutual assistance in debt recovery</seg>
<seg id="79">In the area of international debt recovery assistance, all EU Member States are governed by the same European legislation.</seg>
<seg id="80">Therefore, the method of handling applications for international debt recovery assistance in the Czech Republic and Germany is the same.</seg>
<seg id="81">The SAO and BRH have compiled a comparison of the statistics submitted by the two Member States to the European Commission for the years 2006-2008.</seg>
<seg id="82">The data contained in these statistics did not coincide.</seg>
<seg id="83">Both SAIs consider useful to renegotiate the statistics at EU level in order to find a way to avoid persistent mismatches.</seg>
<seg id="84">Without this, the statistics will not be reliable and comparable.</seg>
<seg id="85">In addition, the SAI agree that reliable statistics should contain more information on VAT.</seg>
<seg id="86">It would probably be useful for the Commission, on the basis of more detailed statistics, to produce an analysis to help Member States strengthen the effectiveness of the fight against VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="87">In the view of both SAIs, this means helping Member States with low recovery rates so that they can increase the recovery rate to at least the EU average.</seg>
<seg id="88">If a Member State so wishes, the Commission should actively participate in this process.</seg>
<seg id="89">5. Control of large tax entities</seg>
<seg id="90">The SAI analysed the legal situation regarding VAT control for large tax entities (hereinafter also "VDS") in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="91">In addition, they collected, in the form of a questionnaire, information from tax authorities on areas considered essential by the SAI to manage this issue.</seg>
<seg id="92">The responses received clearly show that the situation in both countries is developing differently.</seg>
<seg id="93">The Czech Republic has a system to guide the selection of cases prone to risk, relying on a large volume of relevant data (e.g. information from tax inspections carried out, balance sheet data and profit and loss statements, etc.).</seg>
<seg id="94">This ensures effective management and analysis of VAT control in general.</seg>
<seg id="95">The establishment of a specialised tax office for the management of the VDS is planned in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="96">There is no similar system in Germany yet, which makes it difficult to manage and analyse VAT control in general.</seg>
<seg id="97">So far, Germany has focused more on the choice of individual cases in question, mainly on the basis of VAT return data and recapitulative statements.</seg>
<seg id="98">The analysis of these data is based on the different risk management components that will be strengthened.</seg>
<seg id="99">3. The course of the inspection</seg>
<seg id="100">3.1 The course of the control action in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="101">The audit was carried out between May 2009 and February 2010 by the Department II - the Department of State Budget Revenue and the Territorial Unions IX. Plzen, X. České Budějovice, XIII. Brno and XV. Ostrava.</seg>
<seg id="102">The audited persons were: the Ministry of Finance of the Czech Republic (hereinafter also the "Czech Ministry of Finance") and 25 financial offices (hereinafter also "FÚ"): FÚ Brno II, FÚ Brno III, FÚ Brno IV, FÚ v Břeclav, FÚ v Domažlice, FÚ v Hodonín, FÚ v Hradec Králové, FÚ v Chebu, FÚ v Jablonec nad Nisou, FÚ v Karlovy Vary, FÚ in Kralupy nad Vltavou, FÚ v Kraslice, FÚ Ostrava I, FÚ Ostrava I, FÚ in Písku, FÚ in Písku, FÚ</seg>
<seg id="103">The audit conclusion of this audit was approved by the College of the Supreme Audit Office on 27 April 2010.</seg>
<seg id="104">3.2 Progress of the control action in Germany</seg>
<seg id="105">The audit was carried out between February 2009 and February 2010 by the Audit Service for Indirect Taxation and Personnel Designated Regional Audit Offices in Berlin, Frankfurt am Main and Munich.</seg>
<seg id="106">After selecting a sample of cases, a number of Länder were notified of the mission of the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="107">In addition to interviews at the Federal Ministry of Finance, a control event took place in the following Länder: • Bavaria, • Hamburg, • Hesse, • North Rhine-Westphalia, • Saxony.</seg>
<seg id="108">Included were the tax files of the following tax authorities: • Erlangen, Zentralfinanzamt München (Central Financial Office in Munich), Hof, Schwandorf, Regensburg, Weiden in der Oberpfalz, Grafenau; • Hamburg-Nord (Hamburg-North), Hamburg-Hansa, Hamburg für Großunternehmen (Hamburg-VDS);</seg>
<seg id="109">In addition, negotiations were held with the tax authorities Mühlacker, Reutlingen, Starnberg, Verden, Erfurt, Leipzig, Halle-Süd (Halle-jih) and financial directorates in Frankfurt am Main, Chemnitz and Münster.</seg>
<seg id="110">A report on the audit findings was submitted to the Federal Ministry of Finance in April 2010.</seg>
<seg id="111">3.3 Cooperation between the two audit institutions</seg>
<seg id="112">As part of the preparation of parallel control actions, a meeting of representatives of the two audit institutions to discuss and determine the control topics took place in September 2008.</seg>
<seg id="113">Subsequently, in December 2008, the top officials of both SAI signed a cooperation agreement in the implementation of parallel controls.</seg>
<seg id="114">At a meeting in Bonn in June 2009, the inspection teams informed each other of the initial results achieved during the preparation of the inspection, discussed possible audit approaches and agreed on the way forward.</seg>
<seg id="115">The second meeting took place in Prague on December 2 - 4, 2009.</seg>
<seg id="116">The control teams exchanged hitherto accumulated findings together and agreed a timetable for drawing up a joint report.</seg>
<seg id="117">Both SAI decided to focus on: • follow-up checks on the implementation of the recommendations made in the previous report, • examining selected cases of intracomonality transactions between tax payers from the Czech Republic and Germany that were not solved during the previous parallel control, • examining selected cases of intracomonant transactions between tax payers from the Czech Republic and Germany that were classified as high-risk cases, • control of the process of tax administrations in the area of international VAT recovery assistance, • tax controls of large companies.</seg>
<seg id="118">The report on the results of the parallel control actions was drawn up during the June 2010 working meeting.</seg>
<seg id="119">4. Control of VAT administration in selected areas</seg>
<seg id="120">4.1 Evaluation of recommendations from previous control</seg>
<seg id="121">4.1.1 Evaluation of recommendations in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="122">Recommendation 1</seg>
<seg id="123">Conditions for registering payers should be harmonised within the EU</seg>
<seg id="124">Based on the results of the previous audit, the SAO recommended the modification of the VAT registration conditions and the introduction of a new rule for the abolition of registration in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="125">Adjusted conditions should make it possible to reduce more effectively the risk of possible tax evasion on VAT collection.</seg>
<seg id="126">In this context, it was found that the tax authorities in some cases did not use the authorisation to revoke the VAT registration on payers who did not comply with the obligations arising from Act No 235/2004 Coll., on Value Added Tax (hereinafter the VAT Act).</seg>
<seg id="127">An amendment to the provision consisting in introducing an obligation for tax authorities to abolish VAT registration for VAT payers on repeated non-submission of VAT returns has not yet been proposed by the Czech Ministry of Finance.</seg>
