<seg id="552">BpO 2000 foresee a three-year control period.</seg>
<seg id="553">The subject of the screening is all the taxes of the company.</seg>
<seg id="554">4.5.3 Management of control of large tax entities</seg>
<seg id="555">Both SAI decided not to examine individual cases of VDS controls carried out, but focused on management issues to get an overview of how tax administrations manage the issue of VAT controls at VDS.</seg>
<seg id="556">In the form of a questionnaire, they gathered information from tax administrations about the areas they consider essential for the management of the issue.</seg>
<seg id="557">• What statistical records and analyses relating to VAT control of VDS have at its disposal to the management of tax administrations?</seg>
<seg id="558">In particular:</seg>
<seg id="559">• Are there any statistics or records of rates in which there is a distinction between the fight against VAT fraud and, more generally, VAT control?</seg>
<seg id="560">Czech Republic: No, the ADIS system at the current data version does not allow such a resolution.</seg>
<seg id="561">Germany: The tax administration does not distinguish between the control proposed to combat VAT fraud and the general VAT control.</seg>
<seg id="562">• Are there any statistics or records of the timeliness of VAT controls (in relation to the time period of transactions checked)?</seg>
<seg id="563">Czech Republic: Registration of timeliness of questioning with relevance to intracomonality acquisition of goods for selected VAT payers is reported in the ADIS system.</seg>
<seg id="564">In addition, data such as how long it took to inquire are part of the information recorded in the ADIS system.</seg>
<seg id="565">Germany: No, the uniform statistics at the Federal level for tax inspectors contain only information on the average recent check (information on the year).</seg>
<seg id="566">This figure does not provide an overview of selected control periods with respect to individual entrepreneurs.</seg>
<seg id="567">VAT inspectors focus on the latest period of tax assessment; they also have the right to carry out VDS checks.</seg>
<seg id="568">However, the statistics produced at the Federal level for the units of special VAT controls do not provide information regarding the classification of tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="569">• There are some statistics or records of the nature of the additional tax revenue generated, broken down, for example, according to the following criteria:</seg>
<seg id="570">i. net increase in tax liability (e.g. in cases where the taxpayer improperly applied a reduced VAT rate instead of the standard tax rate);</seg>
<seg id="571">ii. only a nominal increase in tax liability (e.g. the transfer of a fully qualified VAT case to another tax year);</seg>
<seg id="572">iii. additional collection of tax revenue (payment of additional tax due due).</seg>
<seg id="573">Czech Republic:</seg>
<seg id="574">The Czech tax administration monitors the number of tax verifications carried out, the amounts of the additional tax assessed by the type of tax, the number of tax entities audited and the number of tax years checked.</seg>
<seg id="575">Other tax procedures (local investigations, complaint procedure) are monitored in the same way.</seg>
<seg id="576">As a separate task, time figures and amounts of additional taxes are recorded.</seg>
<seg id="577">Statistics of general debts broken down by type of tax are also kept, but not according to the declared tax or tax determined by the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="578">Germany: No, the uniform statistics at the Federal level for tax inspectors and for the units of special VAT checks do not distinguish between the above criteria.</seg>
<seg id="579">Moreover, these differences are not distinguished by the majority of tax administrations visited.</seg>
<seg id="580">• Are control areas registered that generate high additional returns?</seg>
<seg id="581">Czech Republic: Yes, the tax administrator has the right to collect the tax payer for verification on the basis of criteria that can be linked to selected indicators in the special ADIS sections.</seg>
<seg id="582">Germany: There are no regulations at the federal level.</seg>
<seg id="583">It then follows that uniform statistics at the Federal level for tax inspectors and for specialised VAT control services do not provide such data.</seg>
<seg id="584">Nevertheless, there is one coordinated approach by the finance ministers of the Länder and the Federal Government.</seg>
<seg id="585">In the ZAUBER database, tax inspectors or tax investigators from the Länder must write down an obligation imposed by them on the increased tax (VAT) basis if they exceed a certain amount.</seg>
<seg id="586">In such a case, they must specify, for example, the nature of the assessed increase in tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="587">• What are the most common findings?</seg>
<seg id="588">Czech Republic:</seg>
<seg id="589">- VDS exercise an unjustified right to deduct input tax for supplies and services:</seg>
<seg id="590">• which were not used to carry out any economic activity under Section 72(1) of the VAT Act;</seg>
<seg id="591">• which have been used for representation pursuant to Section 75(3) of the VAT Act;</seg>
<seg id="592">• on the basis of tax documents which did not meet the requirements set out in Section 73(1) of the VAT Act;</seg>
<seg id="593">- VDS did not declare output VAT under Section 21(1) of the VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="594">Germany: It was said that there were no regulations at the federal level.</seg>
<seg id="595">It then follows that uniform statistics at the Federal level for tax inspectors and for specialised VAT control services do not provide such data.</seg>
<seg id="596">VAT findings are not separately registered by the Länder if they result from VDS tax inspections.</seg>
<seg id="597">However, in the ZAUBER database, where tax inspectors or tax investigators from the Länder must write down their assessed increased tax (VAT) obligation if they exceed a certain amount, the Federal Central Tax Office is able to analyse this information.</seg>
<seg id="598">• Does the tax administration carry out analyses of the areas of control from which there is a high "return" and draws the consequences for the management?</seg>
<seg id="599">Czech Republic: Yes, for example, they are launching nationwide audits focused on risky commodities or the subject of economic activity.</seg>
<seg id="600">Germany: There are no regulations at the federal level.</seg>
<seg id="601">Uniform statistics at the Federal level for tax inspectors and for special VAT control services do not provide data on audit areas that generate high "revenue".</seg>
<seg id="602">There are different views on the analysis process, as well as on the management of cases in terms of relevance.</seg>
<seg id="603">Some regional tax authorities provide special information, but their use is at the discretion of the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="604">4.5.4 Comparison and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="605">Differences in the replies of the two Member States show that the Czech Republic provides a system that collects the amount of data from the tax inspections carried out, as well as data from financial statements - balance sheets and profit and loss statements.</seg>
<seg id="606">Based on a wide range of data, the Czech Republic is able to channel the selection of cases prone to risk.</seg>
<seg id="607">The same is true of the analysis and management of VAT control in general.</seg>
<seg id="608">In 2012, the establishment of a specialised tax office for the administration of VDS is planned in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="609">In Germany, the tax administration does not collect this information.</seg>
<seg id="610">It follows, then, that it is more difficult to carry out those tasks in a similar way.</seg>
<seg id="611">However, Germany's philosophy places greater emphasis on the choice of individual cases based on data from submitted tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="612">The risk management components will therefore be strengthened and improved.</seg>
<seg id="613">On the basis of adequate reference notes, expert auditors must be able to assess the exact amount of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="614">Both SAI agree that Member States should be able to provide adequate financial management as well as an adequate risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="615">This will help reduce shortfalls in VAT revenues.</seg>
<seg id="616">As a result, the return on VAT collection will increase and the level of risk detection for unreliable entrepreneurs will also improve.</seg>
<seg id="617">5. Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="618">The cooperation of the two SAI on parallel checks of the VAT administration met the objectives set by the SAO and BRH.</seg>
<seg id="619">The two SAI have better recognised each other's applicable systems in the following areas: • intracomonality transactions, • VAT risk management, particularly in terms of risk collection of transactions, • assistance in the recovery of VAT receivables and • VAT control for large tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="620">Thanks to mutual cooperation, differences in VAT fraud detection strategies as well as differences in the above mentioned areas of VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany were revealed.</seg>
<seg id="621">The control findings were compared and proven practices were identified on the basis of them.</seg>
<seg id="622">In addition, both SAIs hope that the results achieved will provide an impetus for stakeholders to launch a debate on approaches and strategies within, including at European Commission level.</seg>
<seg id="623">Extremely valuable experience and knowledge gained from the cooperation of the two SAIs can serve as an encouragement for the implementation of future control actions in the field of VAT administration.</seg>
